.  What you\'ve got to do is find a model, an idea of a creature of some kind, that could, of its own volition and power, melt down the barriers of personality that make us all inscrutable to one another.  This creature would be, of course, fantastic (we\'ve got to sell books you know -- I\'ve been throwing around a few ideas...a giant butterfly? or perhaps a man-eating sea urchin?...someday I\'ll find my muse), and would have to work upon people without their ability to protest (for, given the ability to control our own thoughts, we would certaintly suppress those desires that we find unseemly).  You would need many personalities, many avenues for interpretation, and through those many perspectives you could begin to break down the barriers of our own psychologies and express a universal sense of humanity.  But you must have a large creature (perhaps an arachnid?  Or maybe a deranged duck?) that can overpower all - for it is only in a fantastic world that such aims could be achieved.  This idea of breaking down into one\'s own mind, casting off the idea that true communication could ever exist, is one of weakness.  Ruminate on these ideas, Wally; I\'m having a slight infestation problem I\'ve got to look into right now (beetles - good gracious they\'re terrifying), but I will write you again.  Let me know what you come up with.',NULL),(2478,4,'c0eade19ee4d4c26:-5cc5d76f:103579e40dc:-7fee','2005-04-18 19:42:01',0,'',NULL),(2479,3,'c0eade19ee4d4c26:-5cc5d76f:103579e40dc:-7fea','2005-04-18 19:43:29',6291,'I have seen them riding seaward on the waves\nCombing the white hair of the waves blown back\nWhen the wind blows the water white and black.\nWe have lingered in the chambers of the sea\nBy sea-girls wreathed with seaweed red and brown\nTill human voices wake us, and we drown.',NULL),(2480,4,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fd0','2005-04-18 19:39:31',0,'',NULL),(2481,3,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fcf','2005-04-18 19:58:57',4532,'Iokanaan',NULL),(2482,1,'dd6d42e68f67f0f4:-3965056a:1035794513b:-75a5','2005-04-18 20:02:33',2077,'\n\n[A letter to Miss Smith - October 31 (also known as, the day of THE BEETLE!)]\n\nDear Miss Smith,\n	I was interested to hear about your little bike-ride the other day; how very charming that you enjoy being out-of-doors.  I really do worry that you\'ll catch a cold though.  \n	I\'m also a bit worried about your taking to riding so often.  You progressive women go about it all the wrong way.  You try to take center stage, you try and go out in public too much.  I tell you now, IT WILL GET YOU INTO TROUBLE.  You cannot place a woman too centrally in any situation, be it narrative or in reality.  For instance, in my lovely book _THE BEETLE!_ (which benefitted last moment in being changed from _THE FLUFFY PINK BUNNY!_), I certainly allow for the intelligence that you women possess, but I can\'t let one of you take over the show.  It makes the Baudelaire in me (which is, admittedly, rather veiled) cringe to imagine it.  You see, I allowed my Marjorie a good show in the novel, but look at all the trouble she brings to everyone when she tries to think too much for herself.  She makes a blasted mess of it all.  And then Paul and Sidney and the Confidential Agent must devote several chapters to fixing the mistakes of ONE woman who decided to take matters into her own hands.  Certainly, it all would have been better if she\'d stayed at home and taken up decorative-art needlework, or some other industrious habit that contributes to domestic tranquility.  Good ole Wilde knew what he was doing in the play of his _Salome_ (though, it was blastedly boring, wasn\'t it?), in allowing Salome her freedom, but taking it away at the end.  The man MUST reinstitute a sense of order at the conclusion of any piece.  Law and decency must prevail in the end (even if a beetle must crawl up several naked men before that time).  Yes, it\'s all fine and dandy to imagine that women could make a difference, but they\'re so blastedly delicate in the end.  No person wants to read about a woman dominating a text, or anything else for that matter.  Keep her to the background, I say.\n	I\'ve purchased a darling new bicycle for myself.  It\'s green and yellow with pink handlebars.  Perhaps we can go riding sometime.  Oh, and I\'ve bought you a new grey coat - I think you should stick with that color.  It suits you.\n\nDecadently yours,\nRichie\n\nBy the way, do stay out of the cold darling.\n\n	',NULL),(2483,4,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fbe','2005-04-18 20:23:52',0,'',NULL),(2484,3,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fbd','2005-04-18 20:33:11',5297,'Herod',NULL),(2485,3,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fbb','2005-04-18 20:33:23',5297,'Herod',NULL),(2486,3,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fba','2005-04-18 20:37:01',5297,'Herod',NULL),(2487,3,'c0eade19ee4d4c26:-5cc5d76f:103579e40dc:-7f7c','2005-04-18 20:41:33',1075,'the brutal, sensual men invariably believe women are entirely different from men, another species of creature; and very cultured, intellectual men sometimes believe we are exactly alike.',NULL),(2488,3,'c0eade19ee4d4c26:-5cc5d76f:103579e40dc:-7f7b','2005-04-18 20:41:33',3273,'And I have known the arms already, known them all--',NULL),(2489,3,'c0eade19ee4d4c26:-5cc5d76f:103579e40dc:-7f78','2005-04-18 20:49:48',3273,'And I have known the arms already, known them all--',NULL),(2490,1,'894a1cfa4a4460e1:-40a674d5:10357920878:-7fb9','2005-04-18 20:50:26',2077,'\n\nDear Miss Smith:\n\nI read with interest \"Richie\" Marsh\'s recent chauvinistic upbraiding of your delicate little journal piece.  I\'m very sorry in the first that we\'ve all taken such an interest in your private papers, but if there\'s one thing that\'s certain about human nature, it\'s that there\'s nothing more public, or deserving to be so, than one\'s private thoughts.  Certain people\'s private thoughts, however, deserve to be kept private, and sadly these are the people who enjoy being the most public about them.  For instance, Mr. Marsh\'s recent \"novel\" _The Beetle_ seems to be reading that is only appropriate for the water closet--and not to be confused, although easily done so, toilet tissue itself--yet from these very private origins it insists, like some bad rash, at making itself repeatedly public at the worst times.  I cannot conscience, for example, finding yet another bin full of this tripe at the local booksellers in the King\'s Cross station as I wait to take an outing, and the only comfort I find that it is so near to those large wastepaper bins at King\'s Cross that its journey to its final resting-place won\'t be too long nor too tedious.\n\nNow on to the treatment of men within Mr. Marsh\'s \"book\" and, not incoincidentally, to the treatment of men within Mr. Eliot\'s poem.  First, Mr. Marsh seems to have evolved from the selfsame primordial muck that hatched his gender-bending Beetle (curious how the biggest enemy of the intermediate sex scarcely pokes too much around his own home, eh?).  If Marsh\'s definition of a \"man\" represents either the spineless puddle of panic that is Paul Lessingham or the psychotic warmonger that is Sidney Atherton, then I\'ll prefer my dandy with a delicious fashion sense to the neanderthal culture that Marsh, in his own paleolithic way, seems to equate with superiority, any day of the week.  Meanwhile, even though I admire Mr. Eliot as a man of learning and taste, I find his androcentric, solipsistic, and rather histrionic one-sided reading of a relationship to be ample reason why any woman would seek to \"kick him to the curb,\" as they say.  It\'s quite fine to be a person with a healthy appreciation for one\'s own perception and genius, I always say to myself, but for heaven\'s sake, tell a joke, eat a cucumber sandwich, do something--and recognize that there wouldn\'t be a Lessingham, or Prufrock, at all if there weren\'t a doll of a woman like Marjorie to bolster his sad little ego.\n\nSigning myself your admirer, and your inveterate male champion against the likes of \"Mr.\" Marsh and others,\n\nI am, \n\nyour august companion and partner in the rhetorical arts,\n\nOscar Wilde        ',NULL),(2491,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7ff1','2005-04-19 00:29:48',29,'WIFE',NULL),(2492,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7ff0','2005-04-19 00:29:48',22,'Husband',NULL),(2493,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fe9','2005-04-19 00:30:27',167,'pulling flowers',NULL),(2494,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fe8','2005-04-19 00:30:27',152,'collecting bugs',NULL),(2495,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fdb','2005-04-19 00:30:44',213,'stilts',NULL),(2496,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fda','2005-04-19 00:30:44',206,'sandals',NULL),(2497,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fd3','2005-04-19 00:31:50',55,'my',NULL),(2498,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fd2','2005-04-19 00:31:50',51,'your',NULL),(2499,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fce','2005-04-19 00:31:53',97,'my',NULL),(2500,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fcd','2005-04-19 00:31:53',93,'your',NULL),(2501,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fc9','2005-04-19 00:32:08',136,'front',NULL),(2502,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fb5','2005-04-19 00:32:44',128,'street\'s',NULL),(2503,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fab','2005-04-19 00:32:48',146,'gate',NULL),(2504,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7faa','2005-04-19 00:32:48',142,'edge',NULL),(2505,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fa6','2005-04-19 00:33:24',403,'four',NULL),(2506,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fa5','2005-04-19 00:33:24',400,'six',NULL),(2507,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fa2','2005-04-19 00:33:40',432,'My Lord you',NULL),(2508,1,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7fa1','2005-04-19 00:33:40',422,'a stranger',NULL),(2509,2,'c91ab9e973f25cc1:-d69efc0:103589d7077:-7f73','2005-04