8',1368,'There will be time to murder and create',NULL),(2590,3,'789e58e47fa03646:-783b840b:1035bbf610f:-7fe3','2005-04-19 14:44:11',2031,'They will say: But how his arms and legs are thin!',NULL),(2591,3,'39e706a46ad531be:49727815:1035be87e96:-8000','2005-04-19 15:21:35',225,' synthesizes',NULL),(2592,3,'39e706a46ad531be:49727815:1035be87e96:-7ffe','2005-04-19 15:27:22',26,' ',NULL),(2593,3,'39e706a46ad531be:49727815:1035be87e96:-7ffb','2005-04-19 15:29:39',1,'THE RIVER-MERCHANT\'S WIFE: A LETTER\n\nWhile my hair was still cut straight across my forehead\nI played about the front gate, pulling flowers.\nYou came by on bamboo stilts, playing horse,\nYou walked about my seat, playing with blue plums.\nAnd we went on living in the village of Chokan:\nTwo small people, without dislike or suspicion.\n\nAt fourteen I married My Lord you.\nI never laughed, being bashful.\nLowering my head, I looked at the wall.\nCalled to, a thousand times, I never looked back.\n\nAt fifteen I stopped scowling,\nI desired my dust to be mingled with yours\nForever and forever and forever.\nWhy should I climb the look out?\n\nAt sixteen you departed,\nYou went into far Ku-to-en, by the river of swirling eddies,\nAnd you have been gone five months.\nThe monkeys make sorrowful noise overhead.\nYou dragged your feet when you went out.\nBy the gate now, the moss is grown, the different mosses,\nToo deep to clear them away!\nThe leaves fall early this autumn, in wind.\nThe paired butterflies are already yellow with August\nOver the grass in the West garden;\nThey hurt me. I grow older.\nIf you are coming down through the narrows of the river Kiang,\nPlease let me know beforehand,\nAnd I will come out to meet you\nAs far as Cho-fu-Sa.',NULL),(2594,1,'789e58e47fa03646:-305c833f:1035c1d00c5:-7ffe','2005-04-19 16:26:07',549,'\n\nDear Oscar,\n	I\'ve just recently read Salome, and by jove, I can\'t imagine why you bothered to write such supreme rubbish (and allowed it to be translated from its originial French by that mindless dandy you spend all your time with; you would have done better to have stuck with good, solid English).  The truth is you just confuse matters with your endless repetitions that remain as ineluctable as ever.  If we don\'t understand what the blasted moon is doing the first time you mention it, how in the world are we supposed to divine its purpose if you keep saying the same thing over and over again.  Now, I know what you\'re thinking; you\'re already prepared to go into some blastedly boring manifesto about the power of art and artifice and the task of the aesthete and all that other pretentious rubbish.  Yes, my dear O, if I spent all my time with your little play (and who would want to?  It\'s completely devoid of any plot devices whatsoever; just write a poem next time and spare us, old chap) I\'m sure I could discern exactly what you\'re after with all your obscure metaphors and references to peacocks.  But what would be the point?  It\'s all about communication; you\'ve got to speak to the people.  I know you turn your nose up at literature that reaches the masses, but that\'s only your own decadent nature getting in the way of good, solid reasoning.  More people will read my novel _The Beetle!_ than your silly play anyday, because it actually means something to them.  It penetrates into their minds without simply circling around them like your works do.You talk about yearning for a time when \"culture and literature were more whole,\" and yet you try and remove culture from the very people who create it so that you can fulfill your pre-maturely Modernist desires.  You\'re like Prufrock with your moon - afraid someone will ask \"what is it?\" and so you just wrap everything in the enigmatic instead of searching for truth.  You may laugh at my methods, but I get through quite a bit a punch in my little novels, I just give enough accessible surface material that more people can become involved in them.  My beetle is your Salome, my Atherton your Herod, my Isis your moon.  Now, you have written some first rate plays in the past, but better to give up this genre all-together.  Come out of the clouds, dear Oscar - there\'s much more to see down here then you want to admit.  \n\nYour friend (but dont\' get any funny ideas - we\'re just friends Oscar, no matter how many times you ask for something more),\nRichie',NULL),(2595,3,'8009d9e604c33241:195f717b:1035c3d6b64:-7ffe','2005-04-19 17:00:26',5437,'Salome',NULL),(2596,3,'91de22f1aa05b4a6:-33adaa2e:1035c11ed71:-6df0','2005-04-19 17:02:03',4336,'Though I have seen my head (grown slightly bald) brought in upon a platter,\nI am no prophet -- and here\'s no great matter;',NULL),(2597,1,'91de22f1aa05b4a6:-33adaa2e:1035c11ed71:-7ff1','2005-04-19 16:21:46',549,'\n\nMy dear Oscar, I must congratulate you on capturing so well in \"Salome\" the very sort of masculine thinking I describe in my essay on \"The Colour of Life\" when I write that \"it is of the living and unpublished blood that the violent world has professed to be delicate and ashamed\".  I admire the symbolism of your play enormously as you know, but I cannot help but note that it seems Salome\'s great crime is not merely requesting the head of Iokanaan but speaking out once too often. I seem to recall that you reduce her to merely a voice in a darkened theater before she meets her perhaps deserved but assuredly grisly end.  We here see Herod use the word \"monstrous\" to describe Salome when he could equally well use it to describe himself and his own rash oath.  In the end men are all too happy to shed the blood of women rather than listen to what they may have to say, discovering the essence of that \"unpublished blood\".  (Though I can exclude you from this sweeping statement, Oscar, as we both know very well that you are equally uninterested in listening to a person of either sex speak when you yourself might be speaking.)\n\nHow interesting it is that our dear Mr. Prufrock finds himself as intrigued by this story as you have been.  In the lines referencing the story he imagines himself as Iokanaan, which perhaps explains why the women in his poem are permitted only to speak of Michelangelo and to lounge about, perfumed and drowsy, causing our dear narrator to \"digress\".  I think he is afraid of women because of their \"living and unpublished blood\", and is partially afraid of it because of his own suppression of their voices.  I still envision some compromise between your passionate Salome with her violent impulses and the invisible women here...\n\nYours affectionately,\nAlice\n\nPostscript:  My acquaintance Miss Jane Smith has asked me to pass along her thanks for your astute response to that bully Richard Marsh.  His letter was another fine example of the world\'s  response to a woman publishing her voice rather than her blood.  (Though Miss Smith did not intend to publish either and is, I confess, a bit mystified as to how her journal became public.  I am sure I have no idea...)\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n  \n\n',NULL),(2598,3,'91de22f1aa05b4a6:-33adaa2e:1035c11ed71:-6df1','2005-04-19 17:02:03',1799,'the lines referencing the story',NULL),(2599,1,'3081dbc8dece6d31:10de2bd:1035c4bcc66:-7fea','2005-04-19 17:17:48',705,'\n\nAnd Prufrock says, he is not Prince Hamlet, nor was meant to be. Neither then, shall Alice and I assume the role of Ophelia. We will not moon about, or pretend that being courtiers or lowly attendants to Gertrude would suit us. We will not talk of how to wear our pantaloons, and if they suit us. We will eat that peach Prufrock mentions, and cherries, and I want bon-bons too with my demi-tasse Alice pours while we watch the tints of the sky settle into the earthly basin which is filled each day with women\'s work and dreams. As our spoons clink gently against the delicate cups on their matching saucers we bought at that estate sale of Des Esseintes\' a few months back, we will celebrate our worldly words and the new generations lolling b