elf, so I am still a little stung by your criticisms, although I am certain our friendship can overcome them.\n\nMy attitude toward \"Mr.\" Marsh, however, must be more critical and less forgiving, not unlike my attitude toward those carapaced critters that one inadvertently--though sometimes, gleefully--steps on on the King\'s Cross platforms.  Mr. Marsh, you insinuate that I am a precursor to Mr. Eliot\'s modernism, and I say \"thank you for the compliment; may I have another?\"  In fact, you are exactly right, I believe; both I and the modernists among which Mr. Eliot counts himself do devoutly believe that art can become the new religion that can replace such entities as false religion, politics, and other human-made constructs that have been discredited in our great nineteenth-century age of science, reason, and progress.  If you see fit only to entertain the masses like a bunch of infants, as your book seems only to do, my hope would be that you would be at least good enough to entertain them, as I do, rather than unself-consciously hash out the same conventional plot elements time and again.  Please, Mr. Marsh--yet another damsel in distress?  And it may be that both Mr. Eliot and my play _Salome_ immerse themselves in subjectivity, ambiguity, indeterminacy, allusiveness, intertextuality, and a kind of agonized pessimism about the current era, but I know how history turns out, my friend, and I can tell you that our aesthetics and works are those that win out, not yours.  I look at the tired didacticism and hackneyed, blunt language of your novel, Mr. Marsh, and I wonder whether you have heard of our Mr. Darwin\'s evolutionary theories, not to mention the humbling example of the Dodo?  If not, Mr. Marsh, then I suggest you read up on the Dodo, since you and your aesthetic may be headed the way of it, while Mr. Eliot and I shall evolve leisurely into something far more beautiful, transcendent, timeless, and lasting.\n\nYour humble servant, \nOscar Wilde\n\n  ',NULL),(2893,1,'3081dbc8dece6d31:1b939d3:10362b2f8e1:-7ffd','2005-04-20 23:05:43',2077,'\n\nOscar, \n\n  Your charming letters are delightful, if exclusively targeted to Richard and Alice, however, insofar as the Salome story informs your authorial embrace of the buzzwords you mention in your last letter, I\'ve borrowed a bit from my good friend George Egerton to show you how interiority for exotic characters such as Salome is done. This bit is from George\'s \"A Cross Line\": \n\"She fancies herself in Arabia on the back of a swift steed. Flashing eyes set in dark faces surround her, and she can see the clouds of sands swirl, and feel the swing under her of his rushing stride. Her thoughts shape themselves into a wild song, a song to her steed of flowing mane and satin skin; an uncouth rhythmical jingle with a feverish beat; a song to the (notice the keynote here, Oscar) untamed spirit that dwells in her. Then she fancies she is on the stage of an ancient theatre out in the open air, with hundreds of faces upturned towards her. She is gauze-clad in a cobweb garment of wondrous tissue. Her arms are clasped by jewelled snakes, and one with quivering diamond fangs coils round her hips. Her hair floats loosely, and her feet are sandal-clad, and the delicate breath of vines and the salt freshness of an incoming sea seems to fill her nostrils. She bounds forward and dances, bends her lissom waist, and curves her slender arms, and gives to the soul of each man what he craves, be it good or evil.\"\nNotice here the performative power that the fantasizing woman can claim and the actual performing figure personifies. Show us the dance that causes the action, that sways the plot and the reader\'s sympathy. Help us and we\'ll help you. \n\nTruly, \nOlive',NULL),(2894,3,'61ab2bea7f203694:-5742e062:103630be546:-7ff6','2005-04-21 00:39:39',2461,'So how should I presume?',NULL),(2895,3,'61ab2bea7f203694:-5742e062:103630be546:-7ff4','2005-04-21 00:41:15',2586,'nd when I am formulate