k.  While I find your methods for doing so a bit overly-artistic and a little less insect-oriented than I tend to prefer, I must say \"good show.\"  As much as we disagree on matters of gender and art, we seem to be in consensus that solipsism is not the answer to an increasingly fragmented world.  I may not always hit on the right balance of perspectives, but I give it a shot, in any case.  And let\'s face it, if a cup of tear drops had not done Prufrock in, his mind would have created a monster (oh, so much more frightening than a beetle!) in its isolation; his very solitude would become the creature that pushed him to a living death (so much worse than a real one!).  \n\nI was happy to hear that you both are vacationing together at the seashore - perhaps I\'ll come visit you for a day or two before I return to writing my next sensational novel.  You shall give me some wonderful social insights to imbed within my popular fiction.  And who knows - maybe I\'ll make a woman my main character.\n\nYour Some-times Friend,\nRichard  ',NULL),(2991,1,'1ca04ceb76a170d5:19a4d79:10366e386a6:-8000','2005-04-21 18:31:53',1455,'\n\nDearest Olive and Oscar,\n\nI fear you have misinterpreted my \"Colour of Life\" essay most dreadfully.  Though it is true that women are too often called upon solely for purposes of blood sacrifice, I had not intended that we should collectively carry out such a thorough examination of Mr. Prufrock\'s \"colour of life\" for that reason.\n\nMy.  Are we leaving this mess for Walter and Charles to clean up, then?  You know I would offer, but with seven children at home and a festive evening out to look forward to with you both, I\'m afraid I simply do not have time.  Charles will probably take a peculiar delight in this grotesque spectacle anyway, so we will leave it for him.  Yes.\n\nI suppose some sort of final words on the sad subject of Mr. Prufrock\'s existence are called for.  Oscar and I share a deep and abiding interest in the active shaping of one\'s public image.  I believe Prufrock shared this interest of ours, and I can only think that had he been able to move past his endless questions and actually begin to perform a role, to embrace simplicity and begin to interact with this great crowd all around us, his life might have been considerably more purposeful and worthwhile.  I also find it quite appropriate that women\'s tears have played such a large role in his demise.  I only wish that all men might realize that the slender arms and perfumed dresses around them conceal great spiritual longing and, yes, pain.  We are not such trivial creatures as you supposed, Mr. Prufrock.  I only hope that you are now enjoying the eternal comforts of a merciful God and not mistaking ministering angels for the dreadful mermaids of your imagination.  \n\nYours affectionately,\nAlice ',NULL),(2992,4,'d5cd601c6178d124:115e166:10366f21cac:-7f23','2005-04-21 18:59:08',0,'',NULL),(2993,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:115e166:10366f21cac:-7f25','2005-04-21 18:53:58',683,'Where is God?',NULL),(2994,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:115e166:10366f21cac:-7f22','2005-04-21 19:00:01',3,'The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters',NULL),(2995,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:115e166:10366f21cac:-7ee8','2005-04-21 19:00:24',3,'The Sleep of Reason Produces Monsters',NULL),(2996,3,'acfafd8a453ecf6c:1081032:10367050c57:-8000','2005-04-21 19:08:32',157,'Michaelangelo',NULL),(2997,1,'acfafd8a453ecf6c:1081032:10367050c57:-7ff8','2005-04-21 19:21:29',1455,'\n\nDearest Olive and Oscar,\n\nI fear you have misinterpreted my \"Colour of Life\" essay most dreadfully.  Though it is true that women are too often called upon solely for purposes of blood sacrifice, I had not intended that we should collectively carry out such a thorough examination of Mr. Prufrock\'s \"colour of life\" for that reason.\n\nMy.  Are we leaving this mess for Walter and Charles to clean up, then?  You know I would offer, but with seven children at home and a festive evening out to look forward to with you both,