 I tell her she will not believe me. You may remember the old Persian saying, \'There is danger for him who taketh the tiger cub, and danger also for whoso snatches a delusion from a woman.\' There is as much sense in Hafiz as in Horace, and as much knowledge of the world.\"',NULL),(3945,1,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7c57','2005-04-23 18:08:49',7034,'\nI personally am intrigued by Holmes approach and admire his analytical abilities. I have to disagree with the charges that Mr. Poe and Ansel have made toward Holmes\' prestige as I certainly would say that science is not simply a detection of the obvious.  It requires careful observation and concentration.  To you disparagers I ask, do you believe in progression?? The motivations behind my studies rest in the project to reveal truth.  What would humanity do without us analytical, curious scientists?  Are you boldly claiming that mine and Holmes\' efforts are trivial?  I am offended by your disrespect!\n ',NULL),(3946,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-785f','2005-04-23 18:17:58',7400,' The motivations behind my studies rest in the project to reveal truth.  What would humanity do without us analytical, curious scientists?  Are you boldly claiming that mine and Holmes\' efforts are trivial?',NULL),(3947,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7c7c','2005-04-23 17:53:05',2,'In solving a problem of this sort, the grand thing is to be able to reason backwards. That is a very useful accomplishment, and a very easy one, but people do not practise it much',NULL),(3948,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7c5e','2005-04-23 18:07:12',888,'Holmes has the ability to theorize without really theorizing because he directs himself through random access memory of previously studied cases.',NULL),(3950,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7c5f','2005-04-23 18:07:12',1126,' Science of Deduction and Analysis is one which can only be acquired by long and patient study',NULL),(3951,1,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-8000','2005-04-23 17:44:17',794,'\nAs a scientist, I would hope that all efforts are not in vain; one has to begin with a belief in something.  Surely, as you point out, one can never be completely certain of anything.  This skepticism indeed seems to be the strength of Holmes as he turns all the evidence around to point in an unthought of directs--he continually emphasizes the uniqueness to his analytical, backward reasoning.  But, as you point out, this detective may possibly be the worst in the world, leaving everything truly unsolved. I think this doubt is what is leaving poor Miss Alice troubled as she can have no idea of true right and wrong in order to get herself back home.  She is lost on the very path to truth.   ',NULL),(3952,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7c7b','2005-04-23 17:53:05',1141,'uniqueness to his analytical, backward reasoning',NULL),(3953,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-785e','2005-04-23 18:17:58',377,'How much truth seeking does a detective actually accomplish in th detective novel?',NULL),(3954,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-781d','2005-04-23 18:19:44',2379,'The reality of the events that Conan Doyle presented to the detective were only made realities upon the agreement of both Doyle\'s and Dr. Pike\'s stories of the events.',NULL),(3955,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-781e','2005-04-23 18:19:44',406,'The question, of course, is if the reader brings his/her own disorder to the novel or if he/she relies solely on the disorder that the author creates, that disorder which the detective brings aright.',NULL),(3956,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7819','2005-04-23 18:21:58',406,'The question, of course, is if the reader brings his/her own disorder to the novel or if he/she relies solely on the disorder that the author creates,',NULL),(3957,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-781a','2005-04-23 18:21:58',1474,'Is reality the equivalent of the familiar and mundane, and fiction the unusual, fantastic, and odd?',NULL),(3958,1,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-7807','2005-04-23 18:31:42',3030,'\n\nI think Ansel here points out an atypical case of Holmes; however, I do not think the therapy according to Freud\'s theory is contingent upon a solution to a patient\'s problems...the mere process of telling/venting one\'s story to a listener is the therapy.  The process not the product, in other words, is what is most important; therefore, I would conclude that Miss Sutherland still is the beneficiary according to Freudian psychology.  \n\n',NULL),(3959,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-75a8','2005-04-23 18:41:28',3394,'Miss Sutherland',NULL),(3960,3,'f33c9af4a00e002e:16d3046:1037104b32e:-75a9','2005-04-23 18:41:28',2737,'Miss Sutherland',NULL),(3962,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7ff2','2005-04-23 23:34:22',208,'vulgar and unrealistic',NULL),(3963,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7ff7','2005-04-23 23:33:34',794,'Loose ends are tied up in a closing scene/commentary (order is restored; the power of reason has conquered chaos/evil; sidekick, assembled secondary characters and, by extension, reader applaud the brilliance of the detective)',NULL),(3964,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7ff8','2005-04-23 23:33:34',313,'a sense of reassurance',NULL),(3965,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7ff3','2005-04-23 23:34:22',213,'escape from reality',NULL),(3966,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7fea','2005-04-23 23:34:43',90,'classic British detective story',NULL),(3968,4,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7fd9','2005-04-23 23:55:44',0,'',NULL),(3969,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7fd6','2005-04-23 23:56:52',755,' the truth,',NULL),(3970,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7fd7','2005-04-23 23:56:52',4514,'Some facts should be suppressed, or, at least, a just sense of proportion should be observed in treating them',NULL),(3971,3,'d5cd601c6178d124:1b8b5cd:1037242e8b6:-7fd0','2005-04-23 23:57:46',3039,'But