284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6db1','2005-05-01 16:54:35',841,'\"From a drop of water,\" said the writer, \"a logician could infer the possibility of an Atlantic or a Niagara without having seen or heard of one or the other.',NULL),(4140,3,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6da0','2005-05-01 16:55:53',373,'notion that he walks about gathering evidence without first having a theory of what happened',NULL),(4141,3,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6d8e','2005-05-01 16:57:14',207,'Sherlock Holmes is problematic',NULL),(4142,1,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-8000','2005-05-01 15:13:51',33,'I fear that this occurence is merely a vision of Curmudgeon\'s dreams.  How has she managed to so obviously cross the lines between fiction and reality when we have spent ample time discussing discretion between the two?  Perhaps she can testify the groundings for this mistake for my lab observations-- my interest in perceiving life as a  dream or mere precursor to an afterlife has not subsided.  What if, dear readers, there is a bridge for you to cross into another more ultimate life? It seems more and more that life as we know it is merely an inbetween.  My studies have indicated that perhaps life as we experience it is one step below the ultimate life.  I have come up with the following diagram:  fiction--->life--->Afterlife.  Holmes\' theories of justice seem to support the same conclusion.  Perhaps the mystery of the afterlife is what in itself makes our interests are sparked at the opportunity to read a dectective novel.  I at least, like Holmes, am intrigued by solutions to puzzles...the greatest of which is life itself.  Doyle seems to be acutely aware of this interest, and as he develops his characters\' personal stories and leads them to confront in many cases the transition between life and the unknown, he captures his readers\' attention.  The author seems to have a bit of faith in what actually begs an audience\'s curiosity.  He is able to cross the boundary between fiction and reality by bringing death and mystery into his fiction.  The flaws we see Holmes to have especially in \"The Speckled Band\" make the protagonist a little bit easier for society to relate to.  His backward reasoning is enticing because people, including scientists such as I, are set to develop any method necessary to have the wisdom we so often lack.  In this way, Holmes becomes the role model of reason although he simultaneously balances his logic with faith in a greater sense of justice.  He is careful to measure out the limits to his insight and discipline.  I assert that rather than being a meddler or disrupter of order, the detective places a priority on harmonious relationships.  His involvement in cases is contingent upon mediation of disputes--his resolution is a reinstatement of some sort of peace.  Ideals such as love which are important to the detective are likely as important to the reader and foster the link between what is written only on paper and our reality.  With this summation of Holmes, I must say that I have abandoned to some extent my strictly rational studies in exchange for faith; faith that there is one unifying truth upon which all humanity stands.  I challenge you Mr. Curmudgeon/ Dr. Moriarty to consider again how you know what you know...is your evidence merely book sense? Upon what reliable foundation do your claims stand, especially if all the books are burned?  For I would bet that truth may echo beyond its pages into our daily world.  Maybe Doyle is sensitive to our desires for solutions to daily mysteries and basis his writing upon a passion for fulfillment...whether it is intentional or not.  ',NULL),(4143,3,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6f01','2005-05-01 16:09:07',2650,'Mr. Curmudgeon/ Dr. Moriarty',NULL),(4144,3,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6ec7','2005-05-01 16:29:51',508,'ultimate life',NULL),(4145,3,'a21954c284be2a34:9d4a90:10399adeb5c:-6ebc','2005-05-01 16:30:50',2772,'reliable foundation',N