INSERT INTO game VALUES (9,20,'Red Headed Stranger','A game where players experiment with some songs attributed to Willie Nelson on the album \"Red Headed Stranger\"','Enjoy yourself, make fun changes.',0,1,0,0,1),(10,114,'Dickinson Test','To explore the software and the critical approach of deformance.  And of course, to have fun. ','no rules for game play.  although players should attempt to use all of Ivanhoe\'s functions.  ',0,0,0,0,1),(22,114,'The Wasteland','In this game we will explore Eliot\'s elusiveness, a topic we discussed in class regarding Eliot\'s early work.  I have purposely extracted a portion from the Wasteland that appears a recognizable narrative.  We might consider if this narrative adds to a Yeatsian metaphysic of things fallen apart where a center cannot hold, or if it adds something graspable in the poem.  Players should feel free to add or delete parts to the poem as they see fit.      ','Again I encourage players to keep journals and think through rational.  But don\'t let this inhibit any or your moves.  If you want to make a move but can\'t seem to articulate why you might post the move and then consider its impact on the game.  Then record those thoughts in your journal.  ',0,0,0,0,1),(21,38,'Mademoiselle Lancet 3','Third group\'s test game for ENNC 814: Windell, Sledd, Cannon, Stilling, Bryant, Shannon, Maclauchlin','Make one move each day for a week.  Pure experimentation.  Develop a role, try out each kind of action (addition, deletion, commentary, link), post moves and rationales, become familiar with Ivanhoe\'s tools and interfaces. ',0,1,0,0,1),(20,38,'Mademoiselle Lancet 2','Second group\'s test game for ENNC 814: Marshall, Readey, White, Taylor, Bandy, Rennix','Make one move each day for a week.  Pure experimentation.  Develop a role, try out each kind of action (addition, deletion, commentary, link), post moves and rationales, become familiar with Ivanhoe\'s tools and interfaces. ',0,1,0,0,1),(19,38,'Mademoiselle Lancet 1','First group\'s test game for ENNC 814: Sigler, Wentworth, Nemecek, Opp, Harris, Vassar, Donlon ','Make one move each day for a week.  Pure experimentation.  Develop a role, try out each kind of action (addition, deletion, commentary, link), post moves and rationales, become familiar with Ivanhoe\'s tools and interfaces. ',0,1,0,0,1),(23,53,'J. Alfred Prufrock','An effort to yield insight into the connections between fin de siecle literature and \"high modernism.\"','Assume the role of one author from the syllabus.',0,0,0,0,1),(24,114,'The Second Coming','Players will explore the Fin de Siecle themes present or unpresent within The Second Coming.  ','Each player must select an author that we have read this semester as a role.',0,0,0,0,1),(25,65,'Prufrock\'s Love Song','This game will differ from the first, in that one of your objectives must be to play in such a way as to yield insight into the connections between fin de siecle literature and \"high modernism.\"\n\nRule: assume the role of one author from the syllabus.  \n\nIt will also be different in that you\'ll want to keep much closer track of what other players are doing and to respond to their moves with, hmmm, playful deliberation.  Please don\'t bury the spontaneity of the game with traditional lit crit moves, but please DO keep a thorough journal in which you note passing thoughts and meditations about the relations between turn of the century and later texts. ','',0,0,0,0,1),(31,38,'My Last Duchess','This is a test game for ENNC 482A (\"Victorian Relativity\").  Our text is Robert Browning\'s \"My Last Duchess,\" and the game will last one week, during which players are expected to familiarize themselves with IVANHOE\'s concepts and features by making a set of experimental moves.','Explore the IVANHOE interface and think critically about perspective and textual intervention.',0,0,0,0,1),(32,39,'Contemporary Strokes','Half of our ENNC 482A course, Victorian Relativity, will spend two weeks using Ivanhoe resources in a group analysis of Browning\'s 1855 poem.  We shall each approach the poem from a defined extra-textual perspective of our choosing (no impersonation, this time, of the fictive personages the poem names or implies), experimentally emendating, querying, explicating, parodying the text, and also adducing scholarly, documentary contexts, which may be of historical, critical, biographical, and other kinds.  Our joint aim will be to play on the text as on a mandolin, and to play with it as with a tennis partner -- always with the conscious aim of getting to know it, and ourselves, better.\n\nWe\'ll try to shape our game moves in an increasingly disciplined way as coherent wholes responsive to others\' moves, and to keep faithful journals of our play.  Game ends at noon on 2/18/05.','',0,1,0,0,1),(33,39,'Group Soliloquy','In this second game for our Victorian Relativity course, we\'ll approach a different Browning poem from outside its fictive world rather than from within.  (No more impersonation of its cast of characters!)  We\'ll seek to understand the text, and in the process ourselves, better.  Our methods will include changing the poem, commenting on it, finding critical or biographical or historical documentary contexts for it, and staying in touch with each other through the Discussion feature.   ','We\'ll seek to shape each move as a coherent whole.  Moves should be fewer but probably more elaborate, and the Rationale we give should faithfully describe the move from our point of view, not in role, but as class members playing the game.',0,1,0,0,1),(34,39,'Mississippi Confidential','We\'ll work toward an understanding of how the embedded tale of China Aster fits into the design of The Confidence-Man as a whole.  We\'ll annotate obscurities, link to other (brief!) portions of the novel, adduce intertexts, all with an aim of figuring out why Melville put chapter 40 into the book.','',0,0,0,0,1),(35,39,'Holmeschooling','A deliberate joint investigation of Doyle\'s Sherlock Holmes stories, with a view to detecting the clues that relate them to each other, to their late-Victorian setting and provenance, and to their remarkable afterlife in 20th-century popular culture.','',0,0,0,0,1),(42,38,'Pope\'s Italy','~ a trial game, running for one week (9-16 February) and building on Rob Pope\'s \"Textual Intervention\" strategies ~','The idea is for you to experiment both with IVANHOE\'s interface and with Pope\'s strategies for textual intervention, gearing up for more \"serious play\" later in the semester.  Use this week to make reckless moves, explore all of our built-in tools, and uncover bugs and quirks (internal and external).  Use Pope\'s three modes to situate your work.  Get a feel for roles and your journal.  Learn how to make the most of move rationales.  Get comfortable.  Play.',0,1,0,0,1),(43,41,'Portrait Game I','This game focuses on a key late-nineteenth century cultural and literary/artistic scene of writing: what Pater involved himself with in  the \"imaginary portrait\"; what Rossetti and others in the PRB circle recurred to in ekphrastic work and things like Rossetti\'s \"double works\"; what appears regularly in stories and poems from Poe through WIlde.','No special rules.  But this note: in your role journals and gameplay, try to keep clear (and keep clearly described) the distinction, if such it can be, between moves that are mostly aimed at the subject matter, and moves that are aimed at the moves of other players.  Or moves that involve both.',0,0,0,0,1),(44,41,'Portrait Game II','This game focuses on a key late-nineteenth century cultural and literary/artistic scene of writing: what Pater involved himself with in  the \"imaginary portrait\"; what Rossetti and others in the PRB circle recurred to in ekphrastic work and things like Rossetti\'s \"double works\"; what appears regularly in stories and poems from Poe through WIlde.\n','No special rules.  But this note: in your role journals and gameplay, try to keep clear (and keep clearly described) the distinction, if such it can be, between moves that are mostly aimed at the subject matter, and moves that are aimed at the moves of other players.  Or moves that involve both.\n',0,0,0,0,1),(45,727,'Dickinson','This game will be used to introduce players to the functions of Ivanhoe.  There are no set objectives.  Players should utilize all functions of the software.','To explore the software and Dickinson',0,0,0,0,1),(46,41,'Jenny II','In this game with DGR\'s poem, you will all want to be careful about 3 things: 1. that you choose your roles with deliberation; 2. that you fill out full move rationales for your moves, and keep a thorough running journal; 3.  that you interact with the other players (as a working rule, make it a point never to make more than two moves without interacting with another player). ','The game will begin with a text of DGR\'s poem entered by the game initiator.',0,0,0,0,1),(47,41,'Dickinson 2','By popular demand, and after fierce democratic debate, the \"Emily Dickinson Game\" commences','The rule is that every person\'s every move shall be crafted with exquisite care, that every move by every player shall be at once rigorous and imaginative, and that a spirit of Ludic Seriousness will preside over all, and bless your efforts.',0,0,0,0,1),(48,41,'Salome','The final gameplay for ENCR982','Let a thousand flowers bloom',0,0,0,0,1),(54,18,'Demonstration Game','This game is where people can get acquainted with the Ivanhoe interface.  This is not the milestone game!  It\'s here for testing and UI experimentation.','Test out Ivanhoe to get a feel for it, or to try to break it to help us developers debug.',0,0,0,0,3),(55,1140,'Three Men in a Boat','Chapter one from Jerome K. Jerome\'s humorous novel.','Assume whatever role suits your playing style.',0,0,0,0,5),(56,17,'Test','testing creating games','',0,0,0,0,5),(57,1147,'test creation','messing around while writing IVANHOE guide','some rules, etc.',0,0,0,0,5),(58,17,'test2','test game creation','',0,0,0,0,5),(59,1140,'Fare Thee Well','A game played to demonstrate the features of the Ivanhoe playspace.','Masks within masks, roles under roles, and the interplay of knowledge and innocence.',0,0,0,0,1),(60,1140,'Fare Thee Well','Test game to try out the features and demonstrate them.','Masks within masks, roles within roles, the dialogue of knowledge and ignorance. ',0,0,0,0,1),(61,32,'Romantic Demo Game','Fare Thee Well used as a text to demonstrate the game.','Masks within masks, roles within roles, and the dialogue of knowledge and ignorance.',0,0,0,0,1),(62,32,'The Real Fare Thee Well Game','Created to demonstrate the features of the game using a text by Byron. ','Masks within masks, games within the game, and the dialogue of innocence and pedantry. ',0,0,0,0,1),(63,32,'Real Fare Thee Well (Again)','Demo game to show features.','Masks within masks, games within games, dialogue of knowledge and innocence.',0,0,0,0,1),(64,1158,'test game (again)','some text here','roleplay info here',0,1,0,0,1),(65,1158,'nodoc test','some desc','some text here',0,0,0,0,1),(66,32,'Fare Thee Very Well','The demonstration game for Romantic Pedagogy.','Masks within masks, roles within roles, and the dialogue of knowledge and ignorance (in no way the same as experience and innocence).',0,0,0,0,1),(67,32,'Fare Thee Well Once More','Demonstration game for Romantic Pedagogy, November 2004.','Masks within masks, roles within roles, the dialogue of knowledge and ignorance (in no way the same as experience and innocence).',0,0,0,0,1),(68,32,'Once More Fare Thee Well','For Romantic Pedagogy, November 2004.','Roles within roles, masks within masks, a dialogue of ignorance and knowledge (not innocence or experience, needless to say).',0,0,0,0,1),(69,41,'Dream Land','The playspace begins with the Germ text of Christina Rossetti\'s lyric poem \"Dream Land\"','No special rules or objectives other than the usual IVANHOE specs.',0,0,0,0,1),(70,32,'M