e94:-7feb','no reason...',NULL,4684),(430,1,'d6873a7da95bd015:-3769d3ef:10313473e94:-7fea','no reason...',NULL,651),(431,4,'','not much to say','yeah.',0),(436,4,'','Restraint','While our popculture minds now rank opium as a no no for the straight-edge (and oh-so-illegal, so don\'t you try any!), at Dickinson\'s time it did not have the same connotations, or it would not be available through a respectable mail order catalogue.  Plus, opium hardly leads to the wild sort of adventures (at least, outside the head) that are suggested in \"Wild Nights.\"\nI wrote that restraint was admired because her community, backboned by a restrictive religion, espoused restraint of natural desires. Alas, Popcult does not know enough of the country as a whole during that period to judge, but Dickinson\'s limited world would urge such restraint.  Much like those poor, poor children living with fundamentalist Mormons---they will never know the joy of the wild, drunked, college threesome that the rest of us are familiar with...',0),(437,4,'','Dickinson on drugs','One wonders, in our age of perfectly acceptable chemical fixes, whether or not Dickinson would have been medicated and, if so, what effect that would have had on her art.  Would Prozac or Paxil have taken away her depressed, intense, edge?  Would a wider exposure to the world (made possible through medicating her anxiety about leaving her house) have expanded her work?\nThis also leads us to wonder what geniuses are currently being somehow affected (or even nullified) by medications.  Is the torture suffered by artists such as Dickinson worth their pain?',0),(447,4,'','metafictional signal','The narrator tips his hat to the reader/author who might just be drawn in at this point as well. This sign post reminds one of Barthes\' \'hermeneutic code\' which begs the reader to decipher the mystery present in the text.  We, like the doctor, must follow or companion to see what will happen next at the woman\'s home...',0),(573,1,'5f9a82878033df47:-471dbfa4:103185a6265:-7c0a','',NULL,785),(518,4,'','Breakdown','It seems like at this point, the pronoun shift experiences a kind of breakdown.  In the original, it makes sense for the narrator to address us as readers and announce that he is withholding something from us.  But what does it mean for a narrator to say that another character is interfering not just with the narrative but with the transmission of the narrative to the reader?  With the pronoun shift, it is almost as if the character momentarily assumes narratorial power.  ',0),(449,1,'40810c89def84627:1cc892e:103157b6792:-7fe7','Suggestions of alter',NULL,738),(450,1,'40810c89def84627:1cc892e:103157b6792:-7fe6','Suggestions of alter',NULL,60),(519,4,'','A New Perspective','This revision ostensibly retells the story from the female\'s point of view by switching the pronouns and making her the narrator-- but reveals, I think, that more than grammatical substitutions are needed to capture another point of view.  Nonetheless, the revision also suggests that the first-person \"I\" encountered by readers need not be the controlling narrator of the story.  In other words my revision asks: Is it possible for a narrator to disguise himself as a \"he/she\" and disguise one of his characters as an \"I\" to create a false narrator and (d)elude the reader?    ',0),(520,4,'','He or I?','There is a temptation to leave this pronoun as \"I\" for the sake of narrative continuity and plausibility.  How could \"he\" omit a description when he\'s not the narrator?',0),(521,4,'','a scribal error?','Is \"hsi\" supposed to be \"him\"?  (I think so, according to my hard copy.)  This discrepancy raises the issue of who (\"scribes,\" editors, Baudelaire himself as he revised) has been playing with the text before it came into our game.',0),(3028,4,'','asdf','adsf',0),(574,1,'5f9a82878033df47:-471dbfa4:103185a6265:-7c09','',NULL,4687),(575,1,NULL,'where better to indu',NULL,59),(595,4,'','Boat comment','Rather like Ve