e','In a letter to Margaret Burne-Jones, I wrote the following about native Indian culture:\n\n\"And as far as I know, the proper way to handle \'em is not by looking on \'em as \'excitable masses of barbarism\'...but as men with a language of their own which it is your business to understand; and proverbs, which it is your business to quote (this is a land of proverbs) and byewords and allusions which it is your business to master; and feelings which it is your business to tner into and sympathize with.\"',0),(2944,4,'',' on yachts...','dear dj joris and alfred prufrock: \n\nto you, my man, the eternal feminine sweetly whispers: \"oh! if i could only have the yacht without you in it!\"\n\na damn sordid lot they are, those new women.\n\n\"borgia smudington\"',0),(2946,1,NULL,'As an attempt to beg',NULL,144),(2948,4,'','I meant infertile','I have added this commentary to fix my typo. I said that the memories in \"Spleen\" are muted and fertile, but I mean INfertile. ',0),(2956,4,'','genre','What would it mean to write *The Love Song* in a different genre?  (Prose, drama, etc.)  If it is not (in its current form) poetry, where does it fall?',0),(2957,4,'','Underworld','The allusion to Dante at the poem\'s beginning, combined with Lazarus rising from the dead, lends an atmosphere of the Underworld to this poem.  Could we read the Underworld as the Other World? ',0),(2958,4,'','Other World','\"magic lantern\" suggests darkness and Orientalism...',0),(2959,4,'','Dante, Shakespeare','Eliot is presumed to have said \"Dante and Shakespeare divide the world between them--there is no third.\"  Here we have an allusion to Shakespeare at the poem\'s conclusion, but the poem begins with Dante, nicely dividing the poem\'s space between them.  Yet this world, as the speaker shows, is actually divided in more ways than Eliot\'s claim alone suggests: there is the lover and the beloved, the \"you\" and the \"I\" and the \"they,\" this world and the magical Other world, past and present spaces, etc.  Perhaps there is no third artist attaining the same heights of greatness, but what about a third world?',0),(2960,4,'','Why human?','Why \"human\"?  As opposed to \"divine\" or \"beastly\"?  Or as opposed to voices of shades (from Dante)?',0),(2989,1,NULL,'Using the images of',NULL,176),(2993,4,'','My question','This has become my overarching question of the text -- do I see in Prufrock a shadow of my own doubts, fears, longings, beliefs, and desperation?  It seems that here the loss of religious faith is but a piece of innumerable loss...can there be faith in the world at all?  Can there be faith in man when he knows all and has known all, is there hope, is there existence, is there identity?',0),(2994,4,'','Prufrock','An image of Prufrock assailed by the doubts of the modern age?',0),(2995,1,NULL,'Imagine....',NULL,4819),(2996,1,'acfafd8a453ecf6c:1081032:10367050c57:-7fff','rather obvious, same',NULL,130),(2998,4,'','me, yeah, right','Darling, you definitely have the wrong idea if you think I could possibly clear anything up.  Adam Phillips says in his 1986 edition of my book The Renaissance (I can in fact see beyond the dead, so don\'t bother asking or writing and sending me your fan/hate mail):\n\"The Renaissance now looks like what we have come to think of as a modernist text.  It is densely self-referential:  providing, intermittently, an implied commentary and critique of itself.  It is also, through the endless qualifications of its elaborate style, drawing attention, sometimes obtrusively, to its own medium.  It confuses intellectual categories by being at once a work of philosophy, fiction, cultural history, and aesthetic criticism.  It even includes in its first two sentences a hint about how to read it.  In short, The Renaissance was originally considered a misleading book.  If it was seductive it was also, perhaps by the same token, inept.  And yet in retrospect The Renaissance seems partly about what have been regarded as its flaws\" (vii)\nHe also says, \"though Pater insists on the value of discriminating and refining his impressions, of accurately identifying them, his distinctive critical vocabulary is notably vague\" (ix)\nAnd still he continues (trashing me...although we\'ll let it slide for these purposes I suppose):\n\"The publication of The Renaissance, and in particular the Conclusion, was regarded as a scandal of moral negligence on Pater\'s part.  \'Young men\', A.C. Benson wrote in one of the early books on Pater, \'with vehement impulses, with no experience of the world, no idea of the solid and impenetrable weight of social traditions and prejudices, found in the principles enunciated by Pater with so much recondite beauty, so magical charm, a new equation of values.\' But it was possible that in The Renaissance Pater had announced what his near contemporary Nietzsche had called, the \'weightlessness\' of modern men, the precariousness even of their prejudices.  Pater\'s densely eclectic \'modern philosphy\', with its epigraph from Heraclitus (also one of Nietzsche\'s idols), was preoccupied with how one could commit oneself to the absolute uncertainty of continuous change.  Pater\'s so-called hedonism now seems more like an attempt to salvage something from the flux.  The implausible assertion that \'To burn always with this hard, gem-like flame, to maintain this ecstasy, is success in life\' was quoted more often than the devastating beginning of the sentence that follows it:  \'In a sense it might even be saidd that our failure is to form habits\'.  HIs apparently hedonistic proposals concealed a terrible scepticism, a paralysing self-doubt about the \'elusive inscrutable mistakeable self\'.  \'Great passions\', he wrote at the end of the Conclusion, \'may give us this quickened sense of life, ecstasy and sorrow of love, the various forms of enthusiastic activity, disinterested or otherwise, which come naturally to many of us.  Only be sure it is passion--that it does yield to you this fruit of a quickened, multiplied consciousness.\' It was to be an accurate omen of what the self could simulate in the name of passion\" (xiii)\nI\'m modernist, and don\'t know what it is that I\'m all about, apparently, at least according to Phillips....',0),(3005,1,NULL,'Prufrock\'s brief int',NULL,180),(3009,1,NULL,'',NULL,181),(3027,1,NULL,'asdf',NULL,63),(3055,1,NULL,'my comment on the po',NULL,1726),(3079,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:178feba:101c02933ae:-7ff4','Science distinguishe',NULL,4844),(3078,1,NULL,'to correlate white m',NULL,1725),(3076,1,NULL,'anatomy is destiny',NULL,1725),(3074,1,NULL,'anatomy is destiny',NULL,189),(3075,1,NULL,'to correlate white m',NULL,4843),(3080,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:178feba:101c02933ae:-7fed','',NULL,4844),(3082,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:178feba:101c02933ae:-7ff3','Science distinguishe',NULL,1725),(3083,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:178feba:101c02933ae:-7fec','',NULL,1725),(3095,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:74f160:101c61a7d90:-7ff1','',NULL,189),(3096,1,'f0ed2a6d7fb07688:74f160:101c61a7d90:-7ff2','',NULL,186),(3102,1,'ae4829f08456d081:4f8017:101c963530e:-7f48','a hint of nobler boo',NULL,4848),(3103,1,'ae4829f08456d081:4f8017:101c963530e:-7f44','how such a glance ca',NULL,4848),(3147,1,'ae4829f08456d081:4f8017:101c963530e:-7f47','a hint of nobler boo',NULL,1655),(3148,1,'ae4829f08456d081:4f8017:101c963530e:-7f43','how such a glance ca',NULL,1654),(3150,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fe7','',NULL,1725),(3151,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fe1','',NULL,186),(3152,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fde','',NULL,188),(3153,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fe8','',NULL,1658),(3154,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fe2','',NULL,1658),(3155,1,'b1c9c29693f28dda:1c330aa:101ca5c4bc2:-7fdf','',NULL,1658),(3233,1,'9c9694cd2f312628:175ace6:101cb9e40a0:-7901','Duke accepts the imp',NULL,4850),(3236,1,'9c9694cd2f312628:175ace6:101cb9e40a0:-7902','Duke accepts the imp',NULL,1706),(3237,1,'9c9694cd2f312628:175ace6:101cb9e40a