evable.','2005-04-11 20:49:03','2005-04-11 21:10:22',NULL,50),(145,19,64,'What\'s at stake in first-hand accounts?  Whom can we trust?','2005-04-11 22:30:20','2005-04-11 22:31:21',NULL,40),(146,19,33,'To kill Dr. Moonlight.  ','2005-04-11 22:49:57','2005-04-11 22:52:46',NULL,40),(147,20,49,'Des Esseintes describes his view of Baudelaire\'s writing--do we agree that this description matches what is going on in Mademoiselle Lancet?','2005-04-11 23:17:02','2005-04-11 23:22:18',NULL,47),(148,19,100,'','2005-04-12 07:59:54',NULL,NULL,0),(149,21,28,'If My Last Duchess is up for Interpretive comparison then perhaps we should consider the popular interpretation of the Duke having killed the Duchess.  Her portrait is not only a representation but it is a kind of death in its static representation.  We might ask what are the narrator\'s real intentions other than wanting an adventure.  What and who is at risk in this interaction?  ','2005-04-12 09:38:29','2005-04-12 09:52:03',NULL,54),(150,21,34,'What is the relationship, in the public\'s mind, between Modernism and the Fin de Siecle?','2005-04-12 11:44:46','2005-04-12 11:46:12',NULL,50),(151,21,34,'Let\'s fast forward Browning\'s poem into the world of Baudelaire\'s Paris.','2005-04-12 11:49:48','2005-04-12 11:55:24',NULL,50),(152,21,34,'what is the role of he hospital and other government institutions in 19-century Paris, according to Foucault?','2005-04-12 12:11:06','2005-04-12 12:12:55',NULL,51),(153,22,102,'I would like to explore Cushman\'s interpretation of the Wastland as a highly personal poem.  Gender issues certainly come into play in terms of Eliot the poet but they might also verge the other direction into a social commentary.  Perhaps this fragment, sent to Verdenal, is a holy relic from the pre-Poundian Wasteland, before the academics got there dirty little hands on it.  ','2005-04-12 21:10:03','2005-04-12 21:42:19',NULL,55),(154,21,28,'','2005-04-13 19:13:26',NULL,NULL,0),(155,24,106,'Pater\'s ideal Second Coming would be a rebirth of all that was great and beautiful and mythical about the classical civilization, so Bethlehem, the seat of Christianity has been changed for Rome, etc.','2005-04-13 20:59:41','2005-04-13 21:15:41',NULL,63),(156,24,106,'The lion figure in the Second Coming could easily be compared to Wilde\'s Sphinx in Pater\'s Classically oriented mind, and it might be helpful to have the text as example of the original text\'s possible classical interpretations/implications through the Fin de Siecle lens.','2005-04-13 21:19:16','2005-04-13 21:32:35',NULL,65),(157,22,102,'Perhaps we should start thinking about Pound\'s editorial choices as a graspable aspect of The Wasteland.  Now that we have an edition of the edited manuscripts, the deleted words become a part of the Wasteland now, whether eliot would like it or not.  Are Pound\'s choices fascist?  Does he become a slave to his own manifesto?  ','2005-04-14 10:30:54','2005-04-14 11:04:39',NULL,55),(158,23,117,'My role wants to be alone and obliterate the dialogue that the the poem communicates.  Huysmans talks to himself, if anyone, in this game.','2005-04-14 14:26:56','2005-04-14 14:39:33',NULL,60),(159,23,116,'Spying. Injecting myself into osituations where I don\'t belong. Letting you agitate me. ','2005-04-14 14:26:50','2005-04-14 14:40:30',NULL,60),(160,24,118,'This moves is split between my own interests in the sensational and the origins of this text.  I have provided three early versons of the Second Coming.  I have taken editorial authority and left out the lines Yeats strikes out of his manuscripts.  Perhaps we might observe how for a moment Yeats thought of becoming directly engaged in the socio-political arena but opted for a more truly prophetic tone.  ','2005-04-14 14:38:48','2005-04-14 22:19:17',NULL,0),(161,23,120,'To see the peach through Meynell\'s eyes.  ','2005-04-14 16:58:42','2005-04-14 17:01:47',NULL,60),(162,24,122,'To explore the role of prophecy, by comparing a fin de siecle representation of a prophecy of the first coming with a modernist contemplation of the second coming.','2005-04-14 17:58:37','2005-04-14 18:01:31',NULL,63),(163,24,122,'To bring Iokanaan\'s prophecies together with what could be read as a description of the prophet: \"The best lack all conviction, while the worst / Are full of passionate intensity.\"','2005-04-14 18:26:21','2005-04-14 18:29:19',NULL,63),(164,24,124,'If Kipling had written this poem, about imperial India...','2005-04-14 18:38:22','2005-04-14 19:03:44',NULL,65),(165,24,124,'while Yeats questions Christianity\'s expansion, Kipling cheers Britain\'s soldiers forward ','2005-04-14 19:04:46','2005-04-14 19:07:39',NULL,65),(166,25,126,'To provoke thought about Eliot\'s presentation of time and reflection (thought) in the poem. ','2005-04-14 19:32:35','2005-04-14 19:38:20',NULL,69),(167,23,127,'Can we even consider this a work of art or is it a prime example of ignorance, impudence, and poor craftsmanship?','2005-04-14 20:03:53','2005-04-14 20:04:56',NULL,58),(168,23,127,'I, for the moment, set aside the momentous question of greatness in art to ask a question that perhaps should have been asked before: Can this really be called poetry?','2005-04-14 20:05:33','2005-04-15 09:03:18',NULL,58),(169,24,106,'Rome was just as imperialistic (if not more so considering the time and means) as the rittish in Kipling\'s time.  If Pater were to alter the poem, ahem i mean if I were to alter the poem, I would make it about Roman imperialism and the burden and blessing the Roman soldiers gave ... I am at once idealizing it and, at times, noticing its failures but nevertheless cheering it on - who wouldn\'t want roads and running water?','2005-04-14 20:16:56','2005-04-14 20:34:44',NULL,65),(170,24,106,'Making the lion more sphinx-like for fun and I added the commentraay bubble as a questioning of what Pater might have thought the ideal Second Coming would have meant ... an end to what is wrong with his restrictive society, a rebirth of the renaissance, a rebith of classicism, a rebirth of acceptance for sexual preferance and practises ... ','2005-04-14 20:34:39','2005-04-14 20:42:24',NULL,66),(171,23,133,'exploring the relationships between bodily positioning, atmosphere, and emotion in *Kim*','2005-04-14 21:23:46','2005-04-14 21:32:55',NULL,62),(172,25,111,'Stupid internet.  May remove this link. ','2005-04-14 21:50:21','2005-04-14 21:53:23',NULL,0),(173,25,111,'So much of Baudelaire\'s work applies to this poem; dissociation within the metropolis, feelings of loss and stagnation and the onslaught of Time accost these male speakers, feminized by their helplessness.\n\n(Side note: apologies for the notes on the first move.  Silly internet messed me up and I really wanted to post that without retyping. The rationale above applies to both.) ','2005-04-14 21:59:42','2005-04-14 22:02:57',NULL,68),(174,25,111,'Since we cant have a genuine conversation without Dante...\n\nBoth speakers refer to an unknown \"you\".  Prufrock\'s confidence in us may imply that he believes we shall remain in the muck of modern fragmentation and dissociation with him for eternity...','2005-04-14 22:03:59','2005-04-14 22:11:33',NULL,70),(175,22,102,'Here are some pound corrections that we haven\'t studied in class.  What a fascist!  ','2005-04-14 22:26:22','2005-04-14 22:34:54',NULL,56),(176,25,109,'Prufrock\'s ruminations remind me of my essay \'Solitude\', in which I reflect on the loss of that sacred private space in our great cities of today.  Being accustomed to being alone is so freeing when contrasted with the constant oppressive gaze exerted on us within the urban environment.  \n\n\n','2005-04-14 22:46:42','2005-04-14 22:57:35',NULL,69),(177,23,138,'Having seen others high ideas on Greatness, I intend to show my greatness in an ability to not only shuttle one away to the farthest reaches of the Earth, but also to wax eloquently on the Art of writing.','2005-04-15 01:11:25','2005-04-15 01:15:31',NULL,58),(178,23,127,'Some poignant thoughts on the poem itself.','2005-04-15 09:05:16','2005-04-15 09:12:08',NULL,58),(179,24,143,'This Baudelaire poem calls for a change or escape from current faithlessness and despair. Do we think that Baudelaire\'s poem relies more on art and imagination and perhaps drugs than The Second Coming? How is the ordered loveliness and calm that Baudelaire aspires for different from the vision of the Second Coming that we see in Yeats\' poem?','2005-04-15 14:46:24','2005-04-15 14:53:21',NULL,0),(180,24,143,'I wanted to tranform the terms of the first stanza to see what happens to the poem when anarchy does not seem as problematic. Baudelaire did not long for innocence in this way even when he was revealing the the flowers of evil.','2005-04-15 14:54:45','2005-04-15 15:02:51',NULL,0),(181,23,117,'I wanted to respond to the line in the Prufrock poem where the speaker denies being a prophet but sees his head being served up on a platter, so I posted the beheading scene from Salome.','2005-04-15 15:24:17','2005-04-15 15:31:19',NULL,0),(182,23,127,'In an effort to determine how to categorize this poem, I look to artworks that are familiar and, indeed, deeply pertinent.  When can abstraction be permissable and when is its excess disgusting?','2005-04-15 16:33:40','2005-04-15 16:47:46',NULL,58),(183,25,109,'I here try to engage in a dialogue with Prufrock and to answer some of his questions by demonstrating that the city streets he finds so oppressive may in fact be liberating when approached in the right manner.  I offer the woman in grey as an example of the admittedly elusive freedom that we so often feel ourselves to be mere spectators of rather than partakers in, but nonetheless gives us an alternative, a share in the common hope, far preferable to what Eliot offers.\n\n','2005-04-15 15:14:34','2005-04-15 16:54:33',NULL,70),(184,25,142,'I\'ve changed The Love Song of J. Alfred Prufrock into The Love Trap of THE BEETLE - in essence, I\'ve changed our poem of Modernist stasis into a sensational romp replete with drama and tangible fear.  Enjoy.','2005-04-15 15:03:58','2005-04-15 17:02:02',NULL,68),(185,23,127,'Some minor comments.','2005-04-15 16:48:28','2005-04-17 09:36:27',NULL,58),(186,23,138,'The Empire is inevitable.  The important part is to be on the right side.  In order to do this, you have to figure out how it works and exploit the mechanisms of power.','2005-04-15 17:11:21','2005-04-15 17:29:54',NULL,61),(187,24,106,'If Pater were to read this, the desire would be transfered to a homosexual one and the mentions of the orient would mean little - greece or rome would hold more meaning.','2005-04-15 18:10:18','2005-04-15 18:15:09',NULL,66),(188,24,106,'Trying to play with the first part of the poem in a way that would make it\'s meaning change and yet not change completey.','2005-04-15 18:15:53','2005-04-15 18:20:56',NULL,64),(189,23,133,'This move suggests parallels between Joyce\'s *Portrait* passage focusing on the seaside girl and Pound\'s *Prufrock.*  It explores the implications of the gaze -- as depicted in *Portrait* -- and its importance in both gendered and imperial relations.  By introducing an Irish text by another Irish author in response to a poem by an American one, this move implicitly raises the question of national identity and its relevance to artistic creation.  ','2005-04-15 20:18:58','2005-04-15 20:29:53',NULL,62),(190,25,126,'Just trying to capture the essence of Pater to set up for the rest of the game...more to come later','2005-04-15 20:35:03','2005-04-15 20:48:22',NULL,70),(191,25,145,'In response to Richard Marsh\'s sensationalist rewriting of \"Prufrock\" in the style of \"THE BEETLE!,\" I reimagined Mr. Eliot\'s poem as rewritten by me, Oscar Wilde, after I had finished my jail sentence in France, convicted for sodomy by a repressive Fin-de-Siecle society.  I imagined walking--with my body, heart, and spirit broken--through the sad streets of Paris with my beautiful blond boy, Lord Douglas, in a poem that was never written about a male lover and a female lover, but about two men.  Critiquing the hypocrisy of heterosexual society and the cruel modern city, I vented a despair similar to that presented in _De Profundis_, a literary precursor in its alienation and fractured pathos to the fragmented contemporary reality depicted in modernism, at the same time that the poem\'s premonition of my own impending death reflected the existential nihilism and nostalgic regret for a purer, more whole past time often found within modernism.','2005-04-15 21:47:54','2005-04-15 22:17:46',NULL,68),(192,24,122,'I wanted to explore the conclusion of Wilde\'s play as representative of things falling apart. While the murder of Salome could be read as a reinstantiation of the patriarchy, I think that things are so far out of control at this point that the action feeds its own sense of desperation. Also, when I visualize this final scene playing out in a theatrical production, the sense of circling and rotation that emerge from \"Turning and turning in the widening gyre / [...] the centre cannot hold\" speaks to the soldiers circling Salome to crush her at the center.','2005-04-15 22:07:50','2005-04-15 22:21:36',NULL,63),(193,24,140,'Rachilde: I changed the first stanza to reflect my own situation. I would add a longer rationale, but my Ivanhoe connection has been lost twice thus far--just as I push the button to publish. Will explain more if I\'m able to 1) publish this move, and 2) change the rest of the poem along the lines of the first. ','2005-04-15 23:51:21','2005-04-15 23:56:37',NULL,67),(194,24,140,'See rationale for next move. ','2005-04-15 23:57:26','2005-04-16 00:05:10',NULL,67),(195,24,140,'See rationale for the next move yet again.','2005-04-16 00:05:55','2005-04-16 00:18:43',NULL,67),(196,24,140,'Rationale for this and previous changes to The White Man\'s Burden: I, Rachilde, change the poem to explore how Raoule wants to assume \"The White Man\'s Burden\" in her relationship with Jacques Silvert. The import of this \"burden\" means differently with the gender and class relations present in the story of Monsieur Venus. ','2005-04-16 00:21:09','2005-04-16 00:36:14',NULL,67),(197,23,116,'The \"greatness\" for me comes not from art or the aesthetic, but the power inherent in the act of observation. Voyeurism fills my void.','2005-04-16 00:42:21','2005-04-16 00:56:07',NULL,60),(198,23,138,'Enough rambling about what poetry is and what Art is.  Sometimes, at the edge, that stuff isn\'t worth a damn!','2005-04-16 06:47:31','2005-04-16 06:51:51',NULL,61),(199,25,147,'I\'ve added a bit from my story \"The Buddhist Priest\'s Wife\" where I discuss overlapping disks and specifically, how men and women can seem similar when the disks align just so, but really, spun differently (or acknowledging the rest of the disk space) the two wouldn\'t align at all. When I read Prufrock, I\'m struck by the anonymity of the women (coming and going in the rooms) and I\'d like to see that anonymity applied to both men and women; I don\'t see the lack of naming as a problem, but this IS a love song. It is a love song of Prufrock himself unless the women have more characterization, which is why I\'ve chosen to insert dialogue from a female character. \n\nI\'ve also modified the poem directly with a smarter bit at the front; why must Eliot go to Dante? Instead, he is talking about the soul and it\'s much clearer, I think, in prose.  ','2005-04-16 07:50:36','2005-04-16 08:20:50',NULL,70),(200,25,142,'My Dear Ivanhoers: I have stumbled across the most fascinating document - the journal of the love of J. Alfred Prufrock!  Alright, so maybe I wrote it, but I did so using the plays on perspective and gendered interpretation that occur within that most wonderful of novels _THE BEETLE!_.  I\'ve tried to resurrect a suppressed voice here, and attempted to imagine my way into the mind of someone who actually had to spend time with good ole J. Alfred.  If not enlightening, I hope it is at least amusing.  But there are some strong statements made, through the fun, about the nature of communication, gender relations, and silenced perspectives within this piece (which is based on Marjorie\'s entries in _The Beetle!_)','2005-04-16 08:20:40','2005-04-16 08:37:39',NULL,71),(201,25,142,'yeah, so \"creeped\" is not a word, and it\'s been bothering me ever since I published it - so, rather humbly, I\'ve returned to my first move simply to insert the word \"crept\" - good times','2005-04-16 08:41:07','2005-04-16 08:43:09',NULL,71),(202,24,118,'At this point in the game I think we are all exploring our own (or our role\'s) interests in the game.  In these moves I am linking several of the ideas that we have floating about in the discourse field.  This is of course a subtle approach, attempting to create more interaction between players.  ','2005-04-16 09:35:56','2005-04-16 10:01:52',NULL,0),(203,24,122,'Beardsley\'s illustration neatly speaks to the concerns of gender raised by Pater\'s addition of \"The Sphinx\" and his changes to \"The Second Coming.\" Also, to Rachilde\'s concerns about gender and empire... Why must the image of the Spiritus Mundi arise from the desert, and why is it necessarily masculine?','2005-04-16 12:43:37','2005-04-16 13:00:06',NULL,67),(204,24,106,'The sphinx is more dreadful when motionless - is she going to attack, is she going to let things go ... ','2005-04-16 13:07:24','2005-04-16 13:13:36',NULL,63),(205,24,106,'Just trying to make the poem a little more complicated - changing cradle to machine emphasises unease with idustry, adding image of sphinx for fun, tried to imply that WHAT is a different creature and the sphinx is waiting and watching and letting it happen like the birds - perhaps waiting to attack and kill this new travelor too','2005-04-16 13:17:21','2005-04-16 13:33:40',NULL,63),(206,21,95,'an image to ponder','2005-04-16 13:32:31','2005-04-16 13:33:59',NULL,50),(207,25,126,'I did this for two reasons.  First, Michelangelo is mentioned twice.  Why?  What does his addition to the poem have to offer?  Second, my commentary on the lack of nature in Michelangelo\'s work may offer something to the consideration of Prufrock and the discussion of metropolis which Eliot provokes in it.  \n','2005-04-16 14:02:10','2005-04-16 14:15:38',NULL,69),(208,24,154,'What if the second coming is actually the second coming of British Imperial rule. Cecil Rhodes is a bit of a rough beast, in his own way. I\'ve therefore made C.R. the central figure of Yeats\' poem.','2005-04-16 20:51:34','2005-04-16 20:57:10',NULL,65),(209,24,154,'Cecil Rhodes clearly answered the call to take up the White Man\'s Burden. He\'s also clearly self-aggrandizing enough to call it his own burden and ask others to answer the call. Also this poem could easily have been written in his honor.','2005-04-16 21:10:24','2005-04-16 21:16:19',NULL,65),(210,23,133,'This move probes the question of Empire by adding \"The White Man\'s Burden\" as a document in response to Robbie Lou\'s emendations of the Salome story.  What is the relationship between a call to Empire and a call to love? ','2005-04-17 00:03:05','2005-04-17 00:10:58',NULL,61),(211,23,116,'A depiction of a dream state on canvas, in line with Ruskin and Turner. The craftsmanship is irrelevant to me: rather, what\'s it SAYING? Is this life? ','2005-04-17 00:13:16','2005-04-17 00:22:19',NULL,0),(212,23,127,'Let\'s try prose!','2005-04-17 09:36:39','2005-04-17 09:37:06',NULL,58),(213,23,127,'Some minor details in the hope of clarity.','2005-04-17 09:38:04','2005-04-17 09:43:26',NULL,58),(214,24,118,'Asking Pater to revise his world vision of Classical beauty.  Take into consideration the beetle.  To what ideal could this black bug evoke in the mind.  And yet the egyptians bowed down to its image.  But perhaps the recreation of the image suggests the corrupting power of art.   Sensational beetle art can be worshipped as long as it is detatched from it giant ball of dung.  ','2005-04-17 13:15:39','2005-04-17 13:42:26',NULL,0),(215,24,106,'I find it deliciously ironic that Marsh thinks perhaps the creature is a Beetle - the dung aspect is indeed offenseive, but not much worse than the stench of garum sauce must have been (fish guts let to rot in the sun them poured over food) ... there have always been a grotesquery in things Classical, but I perfer to focus on the beauty and mystery - The Beetle, as worshipped by the Egyptians, being the creature reborn or perhaps bringing about the second coming of classicism is ironic since it was Rome who destroyed Egypt when Caesar captured Cleopatra and the ruling dynasty was ended.  This could mean so many different things and entirely change the meaning of the re-written poem and a rebirth of classical civilization ...\n\n','2005-04-17 14:07:10','2005-04-17 14:14:50',NULL,65),(216,24,106,'Changed original text again to question as to whether the beetle is welcoming a new rome or crush it out of revenge once it is born.','2005-04-17 14:17:11','2005-04-17 14:21:14',NULL,65),(217,23,156,'to help prufrock deal constructively with his sexual anxieties.','2005-04-17 14:37:41','2005-04-17 14:55:36',NULL,62),(218,23,156,'to show alice meynell, and alfred, what i really think the \"peach\" is.','2005-04-17 14:56:04','2005-04-17 15:04:34',NULL,60),(219,23,117,'Decadent art, commericalized.  I want to re-decorate....','2005-04-17 15:17:23','2005-04-17 15:20:57',NULL,0),(220,25,111,'This is only the beginning for me.  Mr. Prufrocks impotent existence is about to undergo a few...changes...','2005-04-17 15:18:07','2005-04-17 15:22:03',NULL,68),(221,25,111,'The changes begin...Mr. Prufrock shall live a new life...a better life...a life alive with all forms of city evil, dying by inches and yet thriving in its ignominy...\n\nMore shall come...','2005-04-17 15:22:28','2005-04-17 15:40:08',NULL,70),(222,23,127,'Trying to appreciate the smoke and smog a bit more.','2005-04-17 15:46:06','2005-04-17 15:52:11',NULL,61),(223,25,111,'How I have slaved to bring fire to this poem of impotent circumambulation and empty hours!  My wickedness is Prufrock\'s wickedness and the city and all its darkness comes to live.  He simply has not seen the city as I have, has not had his fill of its pleasures.  I have showed him this and already he has more bite...\n\nAs of now, he is exhausted, but not satisfied...Quid pro quo. ','2005-04-17 15:41:35','2005-04-17 15:59:15',NULL,70),(224,23,133,'This move adds a poem by Pound to complement Eliot\'s.  What lies behind the fascination with water, with the river and the sea?','2005-04-17 16:02:37','2005-04-17 16:07:14',NULL,58),(225,24,122,'Inspired by the most recent exchanges between Marsh and Pater, I wanted to emphasize the already exoticized imagery in \"The Second Coming.\" Perhaps the move is not as witty as one of my epigrams, but I playfully changed the origin of the sphinx vision in the Rue de Rabagas, a \"real [exotic/erotic] place.\"','2005-04-17 15:50:44','2005-04-17 16:07:38',NULL,65),(226,23,133,'follow-up to previous moves','2005-04-17 16:07:49','2005-04-17 16:18:06',NULL,58),(227,23,127,'Trying to pick up some of the gender/doppelganger/selfhood issues to see what I can make of them.','2005-04-17 17:50:17','2005-04-18 14:26:29',NULL,60),(228,23,138,'Responding to Kipling\'s response to Salom and his citing of Joyce.  Like Joyce, Dal had a predilection for the sea the the gaze upon the female figure. ','2005-04-17 21:17:01','2005-04-17 21:28:59',NULL,61),(229,25,109,'Revisiting my Woman in Grey, this time using a first person narrative to imagine what she might have thought of Prufrock had she encountered him during her travels through the city.  Of course by making this move I lose a crucial aspect of my essay, namely the figure of the spectator gazing upon the woman in grey...However, I think this is made up for by the chance to contrast the figures of the woman in grey and Prufrock more effectively than in my previous move which maintained the third person perspective.','2005-04-17 21:51:36','2005-04-17 21:59:08',NULL,70),(230,24,140,'Inspired by Pater\'s move to change the lion in The Second Coming to a sphinx, and the later related moves, I have added Gustave Moreau\'s painting Oedipus and the Sphinx. The sphinx, of course, relates to my character Raoule in Monsieur Venus. But also 1. Des Esseintes\'s beloved painting of Salome is by Moreau, 2. the Sphinx as depicted in the painting is in a posture similar to how I imagine the Beetle would attack, 3. Oedipus! oh so much to think about with Oedipus!, and, 4. gender and the gaze. And more, I\'m sure. ','2005-04-17 22:13:25','2005-04-17 22:29:48',NULL,63),(231,23,133,'In response to Huysmans\'s changes to \"Prufrock,\" I was led to consider \"Let me go\" or \"Let us go\" as a command/plea directed toward some outside captor as a complaint rather than as an exhortation directed toward a lover or toward an impersonal entity as an expression of a wish.  The relationship to the colonies as captives (see \"The White Man\'s Burden\") comes as a natural parallel to Kipling.  An imperial interpretation of this poem could also suggest that love is a form of imperialism.','2005-04-17 22:03:56','2005-04-17 22:36:19',NULL,61),(232,24,140,'Moreau\'s painting gestures toward some answers to Pater\'s question about the sphinx in relation to the Second Coming. In terms of the second coming, what does it mean that the sphinx in the painting confronts and/or locks eyes and body with Oedipus? Might the sexuality explored in fin de siecle literature challenge the Oedipal structure? (I\'m thinking along the lines of Deleuze and Guattari\'s Anti-Oedipus, as well as Didier Erebon\'s talk at UVA a few weeks back. Yes, I sped forward almost a century in time, but eh.) Might this challenge scare Yeats? What about other modernists?\n\nBy the way, I\'m having major trouble with Ivanhoe freezing or logging me off just as I push the button to publish. Quite frustrating, as I\'m not a masochist, I\'m just in love/lust with one (Jacques Silvert). ','2005-04-17 23:24:57','2005-04-17 23:31:14',NULL,67),(233,24,143,'I was motivated by Pater and Rachilde\'s sphinx-like moves. My sphinx is lost and forgotten in the midst of spleen. This might bring us to the theme of memory...','2005-04-17 23:45:42','2005-04-18 00:14:59',NULL,0),(234,25,147,'i\'ve written to j. alfred about the women figures in the poem. i refuse to let the roles defined in the lines limit me or my gender. i\'ll have more to say on this after a cigarette break. ','2005-04-18 08:39:45','2005-04-18 08:42:12',NULL,71),(235,25,147,'i couldn\'t help but insert myself into part of prufrock\'s song. it\'s much better with the additional voice part i think. damn those coffee spoons!','2005-04-18 08:48:19','2005-04-18 09:12:17',NULL,70),(236,24,122,'Hmmm, empire, yes. England hasn\'t realized that is has become Oscar Wilde.','2005-04-18 09:22:45','2005-04-18 09:35:08',NULL,65),(237,24,140,'I incorporated all but one of Pater\'s changes to the line about the lion in The Second Coming into my version of the poem. His interpretation has become crucial to how I think about the poem in this game, and it was getting confusing not to see the change in my version of the document. However, I did not retain the addition of \"the voice\" of a woman. I\'m not sure yet whether a woman\'s voice has or will intrude into Yeats\'s poem. So that change, for me, is still pending . . . ','2005-04-18 09:48:57','2005-04-18 10:02:31',NULL,63),(238,25,126,'It seems to me that there could be more there than what meets the eye.  What is the object of Prufrock\'s reflection? ','2005-04-18 11:46:20','2005-04-18 11:49:11',NULL,69),(239,23,116,'Why do we need other people, anyway?','2005-04-18 14:28:21','2005-04-18 14:33:11',NULL,59),(240,23,156,'prufrock wants to take jasper\'s advice--tentatively, anyway.','2005-04-18 16:24:15','2005-04-18 16:33:25',NULL,60),(241,23,160,'to show DJ joris he is right about prufrock, even if he\'s wrong about the woman question.','2005-04-18 16:37:25','2005-04-18 16:46:43',NULL,62),(242,23,120,'Can the Victorian find God in Prufrock?','2005-04-18 16:39:50','2005-04-18 16:46:51',NULL,60),(243,23,120,'To critisize the many losses of dignity in \"Prufrock.\"  ','2005-04-18 16:56:44','2005-04-18 17:04:29',NULL,58),(244,23,117,'Mr. Prufrock needs much different advice that Mr. Joris has given him, so I have intervened. \n\n','2005-04-18 18:15:47','2005-04-18 18:47:40',NULL,60),(245,25,142,'I\'m responding to one of Pater\'s entries from \"The Conclusion\" of _The Renaissance_ and trying to bring another perspective from the fin de siecle to the board on the issues of communication and personality','2005-04-18 19:15:33','2005-04-18 20:01:36',NULL,68),(246,25,109,'I wish to contrast my description of the seashore in my essay \"Colour of Life\" with the sea imagery ending this poem.  My passage highlights the sea as a place to escape the imposed artifice of the city and rediscover one\'s artistic, natural side, a side I associate with innocence through my mention of the unclad child.  Prufrock instead sees the sea as a place of confusion and death personified in the form of ominous female figures that threaten all of humanity...I cannot disagree with this line of thinking more.\n','2005-04-18 19:42:01','2005-04-18 20:03:36',NULL,69),(247,25,145,'I want to explore how Eliot?s modernism and Wilde?s fin-de-siecle text share a similar traditional literary trope of venerating the wisdom and literature of past ages, hearkening back to an imagined time when literature and culture was more whole, so that the killing of Iokananan/John the Baptist is lamented in both as the death of knowledge and sacrilege toward a higher religious authority.','2005-04-18 19:39:31','2005-04-18 20:05:57',NULL,70),(248,25,142,'Bringing in a new fin de siecle perspective on the New Woman.  Thought you all were getting a little carried away with your progressivism.  Blast you, it\'s still the 19th Century!','2005-04-18 20:02:33','2005-04-18 20:31:02',NULL,68),(249,25,145,'Both modernism--in its somewhat conservative yearning for an earlier, more whole tradition, despite its stylistic iconoclasm--and the fin-de-siecle emphasize the new while also valuing some of the traditional and the conventional.  In this case, Eliot is a conservative author who still references and respects authority figures; Wilde\'s characters pay some lip service to authority figures, but in fact the arbitrary nature and social construction of their authority is shown by the fact that the mighty Herod actually pays obeisance to both Caesar and Salome in different ways.  Is authority similarly undermined in \"Prufrock,\" or not?  I would argue not--\"Prufrock\" seems to reinforce androcentric authority through its confident, albeit questioning, speaker.   ','2005-04-18 20:23:52','2005-04-18 20:44:30',NULL,71),(250,25,109,'I do not approve of Mr. Prufrock\'s reduction of women to the mere outward signs of femininity--He should instead concentrate on what men and women have in common.  Here I use an excerpt from Mrs. Schreiner\'s story to draw attention to this unfortunate tendency of his...','2005-04-18 20:41:33','2005-04-18 20:55:17',NULL,69),(251,25,145,'I wanted to respond to Richard Marsh\'s upbraiding of Alice Maynell in her journal by exposing both Marsh\'s and Eliot\'s androcentric treatment of women within _The Beetle_ and \"Prufrock.\"  I also wanted to differentiate between the high literature and sophistication of \"Prufrock\" and my own (Oscar Wilde\'s) work versus the sensationalist trash of Richard Marsh and his populist ilk. ','2005-04-18 20:50:26','2005-04-18 21:19:28',NULL,70),(252,23,138,'What if the River Merchant had motivation too?  Why should we be so forlorn for the woman who wanted to tie her husband down?  He has a need to climb the wall and see the world.  He should go before he makes the mistake worse than it already is.','2005-04-19 00:29:48','2005-04-19 00:47:45',NULL,62),(253,23,133,'This move suggests that water may be the link between Empire and aestheticism.  When Stephen Dedalus thinks of the British Empire, he thinks of the sea; when Ruskin writes about beauty in art, he often turns to water.\n   Also a meditation on \"Ventana\" as a sort of Huysmans-style aquarium....','2005-04-19 00:50:53','2005-04-19 01:02:16',NULL,61),(254,24,154,'This image from mars, taken in 1978, caused a big tabloid splash. It seems that we cannot help projecting various images out of Spritius Mundi onto any surface we come across, including the surface of Mars. i think there is something disturbing about Cecil Rhodes? vision of interplanetary empire and the imagination that allows us to believe that Martian Religion built a sphinx just as the Egyptions did. Are we imaging ourselves as conquered by martian Imperialists? Do we imagine ourselves justified by the human face on mars to go forth and invade mars? In the space age, I fear, our eschatological concerns have stayed with the popular imagination just as they did in Yeat?s poem. Our projection of the human face becomes a projected invitiation to go to the place where we see ourselves.','2005-04-19 01:44:28','2005-04-19 02:07:29',NULL,65),(255,24,124,'old Yeats\'s symbol seems to have gotten the better of him!','2005-04-19 10:52:35','2005-04-19 11:09:10',NULL,65),(256,24,124,'who is the tiger that Kipling has imagined in his version of the poem?  colonizer or colonized?','2005-04-19 11:12:57','2005-04-19 11:16:11',NULL,65),(257,24,124,'Yeats\'s Spiritus Mundi has expanded -- he\'s not simply an _Irish_ poet anymore.','2005-04-19 11:21:22','2005-04-19 11:25:16',NULL,63),(258,23,116,'If J. Alfred want\'s to take my advice, I think he needs not only a spy-kit but a bit of instruction. In this vein, I am going to comment upon his monologue progressively. In the end, any alterations in his tone will be a result of my tutelage. ','2005-04-19 14:36:40','2005-04-19 14:48:44',NULL,59),(259,23,117,'Attempting to communicate the temporality of aesthetic experience.','2005-04-19 15:21:35','2005-04-19 15:36:04',NULL,62),(260,25,142,'Trying to create a sense of the different gradations of the fin de siecle period so that we can start to imagine how these factor into the development of Modernism.  In this particular move, I\'ve exposed Oscar Wilde for the pretentious aesthete he is - a veritable Eliot in disguise!  In doing so, I\'m making a case for the utility of popular fiction and trying to assert Wilde as a more transitional figure that falls into many traps of the Modernist mindset.','2005-04-19 16:26:07','2005-04-19 16:57:57',NULL,71),(261,25,145,'Since in my (Oscar Wilde\'s) version of \"Prufrock\" has Lord Douglas and I as the lovers in the poem, by mentioning Salome in the poem, I think it is interesting to see this third female figure as not only a female muse, even for a poet of the intermediate sex, but also as a figure representing both feminized fin-de-siecle art and as a synecdoche for the misunderstood gay male artist in general--possibilities that the androcentric, conservative, and solipsistic T.S. Eliot may have never seen when composing the poem. ','2005-04-19 17:00:26','2005-04-19 17:02:01',NULL,68),(262,25,109,'A response to Oscar\'s Salome','2005-04-19 16:21:46','2005-04-19 17:03:38',NULL,70),(263,25,147,'i wish to return to alice\'s clever reworking of the poem\'s end. i\'ve imagined a scene where alice and i watch children play and drink coffee and watch the sun set. oscar, be a good boy and we may invite you next time. richard, don\'t leave a calling card for us, we\'ll call you. perhaps. ciao. ','2005-04-19 17:17:48','2005-04-19 17:34:35',NULL,71),(264,23,120,'To criticize Eliot\'s high register.  ','2005-04-19 17:55:00','2005-04-19 17:58:11',NULL,58),(265,22,101,'IT\'S TIME','2005-04-19 18:46:23','2005-04-19 18:46:58',NULL,55),(266,23,156,'jasper is more than right; alfred needs to be a swashbuckling man\'s man to make it through this world. i\'m reconsidering my advice to him yet again.','2005-04-19 19:16:19','2005-04-19 19:41:22',NULL,60),(267,24,140,'Maud Gonne played the title role in the Abbey\'s production of Cathleen Ni Houlihan. The imagery in Cathleen Ni Houlihan can be productively linked to that in both Against Unworthy Praise and The Second Coming. Kipling says Yeats was just worried about a dame--but what dame, Maud or Cathleen/Old Woman as Ireland? I\'d wager it\'s Cathleen/Old Woman as Ireland, but then I\'m not much into \"real\" women. Dress-up is more fun. ','2005-04-19 19:28:33','2005-04-19 19:44:16',NULL,63),(268,24,140,'This was part of my last move--but somehow it didn\'t survive. I\'ll try one more time. ','2005-04-19 19:49:13','2005-04-19 19:50:42',NULL,63),(269,24,106,'I changed \"spiritus mundi\" masculine breath and masculine world to \"anima terrarum\" - a feminine earth and breath - and I went back to emphasize the she-ness of the sphinx ... ','2005-04-19 19:52:20','2005-04-19 20:01:43',NULL,67),(270,24,122,'I wanted to look at the ways in which Yeats\'s poem both aligns with and diverges from the aesthetic project I promoted in \"The Critic as Artist.\" In some ways it seems as though Yeats has taken this aesthetic to its logical end, yet at the same time it seems as though he has dispensed with it...','2005-04-19 20:18:47','2005-04-19 20:30:36',NULL,63),(271,25,126,'just appropriating Prufrock for myself...Can Eliot\'s language be like the language of the art critic and Prufrock the art??','2005-04-19 21:50:56','2005-04-19 21:53:11',NULL,68),(272,24,143,'Wilde\'s comments on the poet made me think of my own ways of thinking about the painter. I say that the strength of a fine painter lies in his ability to have humans \"explode\" into space. Can we think about anarchy and art here, or \"mere anarchy\" to use the words of Yeats?','2005-04-19 23:01:52','2005-04-19 23:15:40',NULL,0),(273,23,138,'Trying to see through the artifice to the references beneath.','2005-04-19 23:03:06','2005-04-19 23:29:16',NULL,58),(274,24,154,'I\'ve tried to rewrite the first half of the poem from C.R.\'s point of view, though I\'m still attached to the re-writing of the second half that comments on C.R. ','2005-04-20 00:54:25','2005-04-20 01:00:48',NULL,65),(275,24,118,'I wanted to post this move some time ago but got distracted.  I am provoking specifically Baudelaire and Wilde, because both of them seem to emphasize artifice.  In my interaction with Pater I questioned the disjunction between reality and beauty in art.  Here I am suggesting a leap from a grotesque image or thing (the beetle) to the popular scarab bracelet.  I could have also posted some Egyptian art that honors the scarab but I wanted to create a large chasm in which Wilde and Baudelaire could play.  This all still stems from the rough beast passage in The Second Coming.','2005-04-20 06:16:27','2005-04-20 06:44:38',NULL,63),(276,23,117,'Returning to \"Love Song....\" and tinkering with more possibilities concerning time.','2005-04-20 09:15:55','2005-04-20 09:34:40',NULL,0),(277,24,122,'Can\'t help but love this quote. Thanks to Marsh for refocusing me on the importance of artifice, which is one thing I love that Stutfield apparently can\'t handle. Think Yeats likes it though...','2005-04-20 09:40:34','2005-04-20 09:45:41',NULL,63),(278,24,143,'I am yet again responding to Wilde\'s recent post about art and nature. Baudelaire doesn\'t see it as straying from nature but making nature \"more than nature.\" He talks about the need for the artist to be innocent and have a childlike perceptiveness. Will this help us return to the \"ceremony of innoncence\" moment in The Second Coming? Is art lost when innocence is lost?','2005-04-20 10:28:35','2005-04-20 10:35:06',NULL,0),(279,24,143,'I have deleted my change of \"illusion\" of innocence and returned to the original \"ceremony\" of innocence upon rethinking the points I have made about innocence and the artist in the Painter of Modern Life. My addictions to opium and hashish result in my being a bit schizo at times, and don\'t even get me started on syphilis and being 138.','2005-04-20 10:35:40','2005-04-20 10:46:35',NULL,0),(280,24,118,'I want Baudelaire to make an interpretive decision in terms of his seeming duality.  Innocence and Experience, Extase de la vie et horreur de la vie, Ideal and Spleen.  I take the instance of an occurance in nature say...a beetle in the desert.  One function turns it to a monster, another function turns in to a lovely bracelet.  How does Baudealire identify with these two diverse functions?','2005-04-20 10:47:21','2005-04-20 10:51:31',NULL,63),(281,24,124,'what is yeats\'s relationship to authority and power?  is he a god-like fin-de-siecle self-creator, like baudelaire, wilde, and others?','2005-04-20 10:59:30','2005-04-20 11:12:16',NULL,65),(282,24,124,'is yeats\'s (and kipling\'s) self-consciousness merely a reaction to the political and social events unfolding around him?  or was it there first?','2005-04-20 11:16:29','2005-04-20 11:22:37',NULL,63),(283,24,106,'\"the man who would be king\" forgot the -er on brother','2005-04-20 12:06:31','2005-04-20 12:08:38',NULL,0),(284,24,106,'In response to Baudelaire\'s Bit of Painter of Modern Life and Wilde\'s insistance on nature and things Epicurean I would offer, like Baudlaire insists that they are both on the same trach (the right one) and - in appreciation of M. G\'s work - I have complimented him in the best words I can and without the esoteric mubojumbo of the times.  \"The education has been distilled from the phenomena and working principles of nature,\" and his representation of such is to be praised but not for its originiality - it comes from the genius of the novi poetae and their elders.  It is nature in what ever form and that is how Wilde and Baudelaire must make peace ... nature is perfection and art can render nature as more perfect only in few of the many ways nature is perfect.  The best floral button-hole in the best-made suit in the world could be painted by the best artist in the world and the image could be perfection and capture in an instance the beauty of the flower and material  - but a painting cannot capture its intoxicating fragrance or the feel of the best material on one\'s skin.  Agree to disagree Monsiers, the argument has already come and gone long before our time.','2005-04-20 12:09:34','2005-04-20 12:34:42',NULL,0),(285,24,106,'oops, I too make typing errors','2005-04-20 12:35:00','2005-04-20 12:36:37',NULL,0),(286,24,106,'I linked it to the sphinx picture and made the end more emphatic by removing the questioning and doubt - surely no more - Revelation is at hand.','2005-04-20 12:38:52','2005-04-20 12:43:57',NULL,65),(287,23,138,'This should have been a beautiful sunset, but Ivanhoe wouldn\'t allow its placement.  Perhaps it was too beautiful to be kept with in the confines of a data base...\n\nGoodbye from a distant island...R.L.','2005-04-20 13:34:31','2005-04-20 13:36:57',NULL,61),(288,23,127,'To answer my mail (somewhat belatedly)','2005-04-20 14:56:37','2005-04-20 15:10:49',NULL,60),(289,23,127,'On God in Prufrock.','2005-04-20 15:12:15','2005-04-20 15:17:35',NULL,60),(290,23,120,'To make \"Prufrock\" Meynellian.  ','2005-04-20 16:23:00','2005-04-20 16:34:00',NULL,59),(291,25,145,'MOVE 6:  In response to recent letters to me, Oscar Wilde, by Alice Meynell and Richard Marsh, I wanted to show how _Salome_ is sympathetic to both women and oppressed gay male artists; at the same time, I agree with Mr. Marsh that _Salome_ is a precursor to modernism, yet I show that my play and Eliot\'s poem construct art as a replacement for religion and privilege ambiguity and indeterminacy to an extent that they set the tone for much of future twentieth-century art. ','2005-04-20 17:40:36','2005-04-20 18:04:15',NULL,70),(292,25,147,'i\'ve decided to join the _salome_ discussion. i think wilde\'s description of the woman troubling, particularly since the performativity is not foregrounded (as he seems to say/think it is.) i\'ve inserted a bit of george egerton\'s \"a cross line,\" which has a similar dance of the seven veils fantasy, to show how female subjectivity works for new women and how the beautiful language in fact pales to audience expectation and the woman\'s limiting desire to please others before herself. ','2005-04-20 23:05:43','2005-04-20 23:21:55',NULL,70),(293,23,116,'Continuing to educat emy pupil in the ways of observation and assuming power by osmosis. Glad you (sort of) see the light, DJ Joris.','2005-04-21 00:39:39','2005-04-21 00:50:36',NULL,59),(294,24,140,'From Beetle to Bracelet made me think about the life-in-wax image at the end of my story Monsieur Venus. Rather than transforming a scary beetle into a gem bracelet, Raoule transforms a flower-maker into a submissive wife, and then into a wax statue, complete with actual hair, teeth, nails, etc. ','2005-04-21 02:52:50','2005-04-21 02:57:27',NULL,65),(295,24,106,'We have entirely forgotten the importance and meaning and ritual surrounding birth which is and could be evoked here! We have a Sphinx and a Beetle, are they the same as the proverbial jackel in ability to birth a creation not their own kind (for good or for evil)? Why invoke the idea of birth specifically instead of just creation or some other similar word or phrase without a ritual attached to it?','2005-04-21 03:08:11','2005-04-21 03:10:12',NULL,67),(296,24,106,'Well, here are some images of birth to perhaps stir our minds up a bit - or maybe just turn your stomach','2005-04-21 03:20:38','2005-04-21 03:25:46',NULL,67),(297,24,106,'I don\'t know what this is - I thought I published all my moves before I tried to exit ...','2005-04-21 03:26:54','2005-04-21 03:29:38',NULL,67),(298,24,140,'The beetle bracelet is lovely, sure. But the wax figure of Jacques at the end of my story is much creepier, no? It encases his actual 