resages  Stein,  Otto Weineger, & the race theorists.\n\n','2005-03-07 01:15:42','2005-03-07 01:31:14',NULL,5),(606,44,312,'I enter some texts into the field which portray \'fair faces that art not.\'  Although all are state-of-the-art cultural products, their decadence and their subtle social critique--which belies their apparently self-referential fashionableness--remind me of poetry of a certain era...one \'Pure Sound\' poet in particular...','2005-03-07 19:39:27','2005-03-07 19:56:00',NULL,8),(607,43,319,'Look at me now and here I am.','2005-03-07 11:51:45','2005-03-07 12:00:10',NULL,6),(608,44,329,'A note expressing gratitude and containing judicious foreshadowing.','2005-03-07 20:09:23','2005-03-07 20:12:36',NULL,8),(609,44,329,'A few selections that I find particularly apt for our publication.  More specific comments to follow.  ','2005-03-08 15:25:37','2005-03-08 15:57:04',NULL,8),(610,43,322,'I\'m going to take up the issue of race & aesthetics. First I\'ll connect Manet and Rossetti, roughly contemporaries of one another--each associated with the avant-garde--one in Paris, the other in London by posting Manet?s Olympia and Rossetti?s Beloved. Rossetti had just been to Paris where he viewed Manet?s Olympia and was no doubt witness to the intense public outrage that it occasioned. Notice in Rossetti\'s Beloved the black figure. As Rossetti said, he liked to think of his paintings in terms of jewels and commented that the ?jett? was essential. Problematically it seems then that the African figure serves as a decorative device to set off the white figures-signifying the aesthetic superiority of the European beauty. Now consider Manet\'s Olympia: It?s more difficult to pin down as Olympia herself had caused much consternation among the viewing public who claimed Manet had created a \"monkey\" by depicting a proletarian whore. She has none of the mystic of Ingres? otherwordly Olympia figure. She has only her labor power. In the 1860s prostitutes and black women were considered by science to have congenitally deformed genitals that predisposed them to have a hypersexuality. ','2005-03-08 21:09:11','2005-03-08 21:31:12',NULL,5),(611,43,322,'With my long historical memory long historical memory I can draw a connection between Titian and Manet.Why I remember those salon exhibitions as if they were yesterday!\n\nI\'ve added Titian\'s Venus of Urbino.One can see that it?s the standard from which Manet made his innovative Olympia. The reclining nude is soft, without definite musculature and her hand drifts between her legs, starkly different from Olympia, who firmly covers herself. Venus\'s gaze is unfocused. Her white attendant is in the background, blending into the sumptuous surroundings.\n','2005-03-08 21:33:42','2005-03-08 21:46:45',NULL,5),(612,43,319,'\"...subject and object are unsuitable names here. They keep us from thinking precisely this ambiguous nature.\"','2005-03-08 21:43:47','2005-03-08 22:17:56',NULL,6),(613,43,319,'\"However, by its self-sufficient presence the work of art is similar rather to the mere thing which has taken shape by itself and is self-contained. Nevertheless we do not count such works among mere things.\"','2005-03-08 22:38:21','2005-03-08 22:50:40',NULL,4),(614,43,322,'Shameless objects/shameful objects. Icons speak louder than words.\nAn avatar introduced Freud\'s Uncanny. Amazingly useful to my project (like the arcades, an unfinished maze) I\'ve entered into a dialogue with Athena , Aphrodite, Hera, and London.','2005-03-08 22:32:32','2005-03-08 22:59:07',NULL,6),(615,43,332,'\"Signifier of the signifier of the signified\"?  City of Lights, why so in the dark?  A quick peek into the card catalog yields the answer you seek.  Note the reclining, sexually-enabled woman and subservient gazes a la Manet\'s work.  Perhaps Hollywood has something important to say about portraiture.','2005-03-09 10:23:47','2005-03-09 11:01:35',NULL,6),(616,43,331,'In our progression toward selfhood, each of us paints a self-portrait.  I submit these pieces not as representations of selves but as iconic representations of the creation of selves.  The gaze defines the imaginary self; the reclining binds us to the womb/crib infancy of the real.  The always unbridged gap between creator and created, self and self, aches with lack.','2005-03-09 13:45:17','2005-03-09 14:36:35',NULL,5),(617,43,319,'\"But since it is a matter here of direct description, it may be well to facilitate the visual realization of them. For this purpose a pictorial representation suffices. We shall choose a well-known painting by Van Gogh, who painted such shoes several times. But what is there to see here?\"','2005-03-10 13:09:24','2005-03-10 13:45:49',NULL,6),(618,43,319,'\"Usefulness is the basic feature from which this entity regards us, that is, flashes at us and thereby is present and thus is this entity.\"','2005-03-10 13:50:07','2005-03-10 13:53:19',NULL,4),(619,43,336,'To add some suggestive and some not-so-suggestive commentary to the images.  ','2005-03-10 14:33:33','2005-03-10 14:52:09',NULL,5),(620,43,336,'this should have been attatched to my last move','2005-03-10 15:02:14','2005-03-10 15:05:05',NULL,4),(621,44,338,'To focus on Rossetti\'s portrait of Helen.','2005-03-10 17:37:11','2005-03-10 17:40:28',NULL,9),(622,44,329,'I determine the worthiness of the submitted poem.','2005-03-10 22:41:56','2005-03-10 22:44:02',NULL,9),(623,44,339,'To begin a commentary with some of the text in the field, as its unclear how they fit into the topic at hand in the game...','2005-03-11 00:41:09','2005-03-11 01:01:10',NULL,9),(624,43,336,'To pose a question: Who does portraiture modify more the subject or the artist?  Who dies and who lives?  ','2005-03-11 12:27:51','2005-03-11 12:39:53',NULL,6),(625,44,343,'The relationship between death and the portrait. Who really dies so that the portrait may be born? The subject (which is to say--the object) of the portrait, or its author? How does this relate to ekphrasis? Does ekphrasis rob from the visually rich, to give to the visually poor? Or is it the visual \"text\" which is enlivened by inflating it with verbiage?','2005-03-11 18:49:17','2005-03-11 19:12:28',NULL,8),(626,44,343,'More of Master Hector Frasis\'s materials, presented by his obedient valet, Pedro.','2005-03-11 19:19:07','2005-03-11 19:26:54',NULL,8),(627,44,343,'Helen herself enters the field!','2005-03-11 19:47:32','2005-03-11 19:56:30',NULL,9),(628,44,339,'Why does a \"portrait\"--imaginary or otherwise--conjure such a limited aesthetic?  Let\'s gaze upon the bitter and vicious \'lovliness\' of faces that are as common and as cheap as the morality of reviewers.','2005-03-11 20:48:54','2005-03-12 02:15:49',NULL,9),(629,43,319,'\"Yet knowing does not consist in mere information and notions about something. He who truly knows what is, knows what he wills to do in the midst of what is.\"','2005-03-12 12:26:10','2005-03-12 12:32:43',NULL,5),(630,44,329,'Cowper creates a vivid portraiture that Clare is uncapable of doing--but I\'ll simply post his work and express my dissatisfation.  I shall leave it to you, read reader, to determine the worthier poem.','2005-03-12 15:39:47','2005-03-13 01:44:03',NULL,9),(631,43,322,'In response to the librarian\'s crude move: I\'ve posted the physical object: The dust jacket of The Making of Americans. It completes one of my cycles--detailing the hermeneutics of identity and representation. The book shares an identity with the call number and with the physical text itself. The call no. signifies the book which, in turn, is composed of linguistic signifiers, another representational scheme that produces meaning, narrative, value, i.e. the Making of Americans as we know it. The call number is the third signifier, the intermediary sign system that links physical object (culturally readable) to literary object (functionally & culturally redeadable). Unless one knows to what the call number refers it remains indecipherable, it remains in the realm of mathematical or scientific language: classificatory, evaulative with out valuation. \n   Poor librarian, where is your baedeker? Why assume Steinbeck? Has a middle school syllabus clouded your judgment? Database running on 1.0? A city is complex, think of it as a linguistic object, it can be entered at many points, and there is no \"answer\" as there has never been a \"question.\" Meaning unravels & undoes itself within those very propositions that enable it. Do you not remember, the EVIDENCE ALWAYS CONTRADICTS.\n','2005-03-12 15:35:31','2005-03-12 15:56:30',NULL,6),(632,43,322,'Visual signifiers are no more transparent than verbal signifiers. A caution in regards to interpretation. A comment on the promiscuity of the archive','2005-03-12 15:57:45','2005-03-12 16:45:59',NULL,6),(633,44,345,'To use early nineteenth-century art criticism as a way of thinking \"outside the box\"...','2005-03-12 18:21:28','2005-03-12 18:37:09',NULL,9),(634,43,322,'My last move got garbled. Somehow my commentary didn\'t appear although the move rationale did. Also, some images which I had added then dumped in the garbage can, planning to use them in a separate move, did appear alongside the ghost commentary. So, I\'m trying my best to clean up the scramble.','2005-03-12 17:10:49','2005-03-15 16:03:48',NULL,6),(635,43,332,'City of confusion!  In the same breath you both curse me for delivering an object and supply one of your own?  Mon amie, you cannot have it both ways!  No city but a maze, and you are its Daedalus.  Our government committees, sub-committees, officials, analysts, and incontrovertible experts have prescribed the proper course...why dawdle over silly word games?  Or perhaps you are disconcerted only with having your trap sprung early?  Surely you know that you are not the only one painting your portrait.  This old librarian has seen too many bloody recall battles to squabble with moon-eyed deviants, though.  Here, then, a peace offering.  Two portraits by the lauded Sr. Goya: one fit only for the most shamelessly prurient of minds--not that you, dear Paris, would know anything about that--and another, tasteful version for the more upstanding among us.  Choose wisely!','2005-03-13 00:00:31','2005-03-13 00:19:21',NULL,4),(636,44,329,'Two ekphrastic selections; two lovely blazons that demonstrate that even vulgar writers are capable of elevated literary portraiture.','2005-03-13 02:08:45','2005-03-13 02:13:04',NULL,9),(637,44,329,'Simply a bit of tidying up.','2005-03-13 02:14:15','2005-03-13 02:16:26',NULL,7),(638,43,319,'A bit of role reversal, shall we? Turn about is fair play on the wheel o\' discourse. How\'d you like it if I deformed you?','2005-03-13 16:13:48','2005-03-13 16:29:28',NULL,5),(639,44,329,'More texts that may apply better focus to Mr. Hatchard\'s project.','2005-03-14 01:38:01','2005-03-14 01:40:29',NULL,8),(640,44,329,'Adding texts that Ivanhow seems to have, at least initially, ignored.  Perhaps, too, the beginning of the discussion of the literary/imaginary/ekphrastic portrait from the vantage of their creators.','2005-03-14 01:42:07','2005-03-14 01:48:08',NULL,8),(641,43,309,'making shoe portraits; repeating reflection on repeating; dissing and simplifying and complexifying la can','2005-03-14 09:27:39','2005-03-14 09:43:54',NULL,6),(642,43,315,'\"Watteau seems to be questioning\nwhether the situation is, after all, so hilarious. He asks us, also, I think, to consider the differences between the way we are seen, the way we present ourselves, and the way we really are.\"\nSister Wendy\'s American  Masterpieces','2005-03-14 12:58:54','2005-03-14 13:06:59',NULL,6),(643,44,338,'To extend the portaiture of Helen in ballad form.  ','2005-03-14 13:36:05','2005-03-14 13:42:33',NULL,9),(644,43,315,'On tiptoeing with big old boots. BananaRepublic, fashion, shoes, and the construction of a self-portrait today. What do Van Gogh\'s boots and Banana\'s have in common? How do they mirror each other? On the work of art in the age of mechanical reproduction. On new shoes versus old shoes. On auras. On self-fashioning as self-portraiture. ','2005-03-14 13:29:55','2005-03-14 13:43:08',NULL,6),(645,43,315,'Jenny deformed and her sister Roxanne. Some moral / aesthetic comments on previous moves by a Policeman.','2005-03-14 13:50:43','2005-03-14 14:05:17',NULL,6),(646,43,309,'The portrait speaks to Dorian, curiously in the voice of Stein. Dorian\'s adventures in recreational-to-professional drug use recast the story. What can this strange speaking portrait possibly mean? How do the mechanics of the painted canvas let it speak so?','2005-03-14 13:44:40','2005-03-14 14:14:28',NULL,6),(647,44,338,'To espose a grotesque portrait of Salome.  ','2005-03-14 14:31:20','2005-03-14 14:33:46',NULL,8),(648,43,315,'\"There are two essetial questions everybody would think about right away when searching for the artist: Who that artist would be? and How much would it cost?\"','2005-03-14 14:39:37','2005-03-14 14:44:52',NULL,6),(649,43,309,'Jenny, I got a new feeling now, you been teaching to me, just like I told you once, just like a new religion to me, and I see perhaps what really loving is like, like really having everything together, new things, little pieces all different, like I always before been thinking was bad to be having, all go together like, to make one good big feeling. ','2005-03-14 14:37:17','2005-03-14 14:48:19',NULL,6),(650,43,315,'\"And in sooth some who beheld the portrait spoke of its resemblance in low words\"','2005-03-14 14:46:58','2005-03-14 15:07:32',NULL,6),(651,43,309,'added a fourth comparison to \"3 comparisons\"','2005-03-14 15:08:08','2005-03-14 15:09:24',NULL,6),(652,43,309,'modern-day composition as explanation?','2005-03-14 15:24:20','2005-03-14 15:26:30',NULL,6),(653,43,336,'To focus more on portraiture on Death.  Le Mezzetin has suggested this discourse with his move \"The Oval Portrait.\"  What death occurs in art, especially portraiture?  ','2005-03-14 16:33:17','2005-03-14 16:53:42',NULL,6),(654,43,319,'My own little deformance. My own oval portrait. And some subtle prodding for the rest of you discourse litterbugs. I feel like I have document-acne because of you all -- and what have you learned from it? Gertrude Stein, Jacques Lacan, John Milton, Oscar Wilde, Edgar Allen Poe, Martin Heidegger -- what am I, your bookshelf? Why don\'t you all go back to the listserve and clutter up your OWN inboxes? \n\nSpeaking from an inner standing point.','2005-03-14 17:16:07','2005-03-14 17:56:45',NULL,6),(655,43,309,'Avatar Avatar Borges Borges Menard Quixote','2005-03-15 12:04:02','2005-03-15 12:05:49',NULL,4),(656,43,309,'attached to the last move, but separated because of the image/text move separations Prof. McGann advised us to make (because of software glitches)','2005-03-15 12:06:35','2005-03-15 12:08:35',NULL,4),(657,44,345,'A mind-blow-job: to imagine some kind of oral relief (/aural/visual) from blindness and remembered desire.','2005-03-15 14:36:49','2005-03-15 14:38:21',NULL,7),(658,43,319,'Morgan is gone, but his Avatar lives on. Beheaded and elegantly ruffed---it transcends the merely physical but celebrates the senses. Eyes closed, because it rejects the visual to which your subject-centered oppression confines it. A transcendental id and a phenomenological object. \n\nAfter the revolution, it will be Cervantes who is seen to be imitating Menard---but both are only botched portraits of the Quixote. In memory of the deceased, this simulacrum offers a last philosophical quote. Baudrillard will have been our prophet, when the empire rots. Long live the Map!','2005-03-15 14:21:02','2005-03-15 14:47:14',NULL,6),(659,43,322,'To \"close\" the Olympia cycle: A photograph and a portrait of the beautiful and deformed Bette Lou Williams. Le Mezzetin brought an important distinction to light??the difference between the camera and the artist, between lifelike or photographic accuracey and realism. Also, like descriptions of Le Mezzetin, who \"never belonged\" these portraits intensify the real and the ideal and share something of the identity of le Mezzetin: For Williams\' Other, her appendage, her parasite, half her own, this self without a voice, who was always \"alien\" and to Williams, shuttled off to freak shows treated as though she were \"alien\"...\n  in effect an alphalpha field for Lacan (fertile field of inquiry=\"alphalpha\"). What to do with a subject that carries her own presymbolic? Not an other but a parasitic other? The photograph would have Bette be entirely \"Other\" and yet has sympathy for her. The portrait complicates the situation, offering the subject (all of the subject) as an aesthetic object.','2005-03-15 16:27:54','2005-03-15 16:51:06',NULL,5),(660,44,339,'A few stray comments to keep the field from becoming too...Victorian.','2005-03-15 19:47:31','2005-03-15 20:56:04',NULL,9),(661,44,329,'The typesetter needs to cast off his copy, so he needs a preliminary listing of titles.  Enclosed are my comments on the work submitted by others.  A provisional table should be available tomorrow.  Thank you for your time.  JH.','2005-03-15 19:58:00','2005-03-15 20:40:12',NULL,9),(662,44,338,'What do these painted women ask of us?  How are they triumphant from within the canvas, or are they?','2005-03-15 19:41:50','2005-03-15 20:44:46',NULL,8),(663,44,338,'To explore Helen, dead and alive, ugly and lovely; to crowd her many versions together into a clump of angry truth.  ','2005-03-15 20:49:46','2005-03-15 20:57:30',NULL,7),(664,44,338,'','2005-03-15 21:09:34',NULL,NULL,0),(665,44,353,'To question the efficacy and morality of portraiture','2005-03-16 00:31:18','2005-03-16 02:44:33',NULL,7),(666,44,353,'To reintroduce My Last Duchess into our conversation.','2005-03-16 02:51:09','2005-03-16 02:53:49',NULL,9),(667,44,353,'To introduce the relationship between portraiture and spectrality; to what extent do portraits conjure up ghosts from the past? And how do these ghosts 