rd and Amherst?\n\nSorry to clutter up your game with a non-move like this. I really mean to do something really good soon.','2005-04-18 23:47:26','2005-04-19 00:10:18',NULL,17),(705,47,387,'To remind Mr. Kaufmann he is NOBODY.  ','2005-04-19 17:09:13','2005-04-19 17:25:47',NULL,17),(706,47,387,'To show Gertrude a poem about food and rooms.  ','2005-04-19 17:27:35','2005-04-19 17:30:40',NULL,17),(707,47,387,'To illuminate the Higginson-Dickinson relationship with a modern parallel.  ','2005-04-19 17:33:48','2005-04-19 17:38:15',NULL,17),(708,47,399,'To recenter us on \"Because I Could Not Stop for Death\" by changing Kaufman\'s/Dickinson\'s \"Hope\" to \"Death.\" To recast death as a bird whose chirping asks \"not a crumb\" of the individual but whose noise persists, retreating in busy times but reemerging in moments of quiet and solitude. To render death an ever-present force in life. ','2005-04-19 17:39:34','2005-04-19 18:04:05',NULL,18),(709,47,399,'To challenge our current game and our thinking, which has stagnated over these editorial concerns. To introduce harsh reality into our heady debate. To channel (and perhaps to ventriloquize) the political concerns of my departmental doppelganger. To write a miniature manifesto, because others have, and I feel excluded:(','2005-04-19 18:53:45','2005-04-19 19:03:01',NULL,17),(710,47,383,'This game needs a summary and so I have provided one.   It seems self-explanatory as numbers usually are.','2005-04-19 20:18:58','2005-04-19 20:35:44',NULL,18),(711,47,406,'Some dark motives behind some editoral decisions. The Mabel Case. A lawsuit. Lavinia versus Mabel. The daughter enters the field. The Dickinson that results out of this. ','2005-04-19 20:28:18','2005-04-19 20:34:08',NULL,18),(712,47,406,'The tune of the lock. The story continues.','2005-04-19 20:36:35','2005-04-19 20:38:00',NULL,18),(713,47,406,'LUDICrous!','2005-04-19 20:51:53','2005-04-19 20:53:35',NULL,18),(714,47,405,'Emiy in my pocket. Very personal editors. Sentimental rationales for editorial choices or not all that glitters is gold. ','2005-04-19 20:59:55','2005-04-19 21:03:14',NULL,17),(715,47,399,'To make us think of Dickinson\'s poem as a philosophical treatise, as a profound meditation upon life and death. To cease, along with Susan Howe, the \"diminutivizing\" and domestication of Dickinson. ','2005-04-19 20:00:33','2005-04-19 21:29:43',NULL,17),(716,47,405,'','2005-04-19 21:06:57',NULL,NULL,17),(717,47,407,'Mrs. Todd\'s ways of presenting Dickinson to her women readers. The first steps in creating \"Emily\". ','2005-04-19 21:45:05','2005-04-19 21:47:33',NULL,18),(718,47,407,'Other ways of understanding edition. THe creation of ED in the 1890s by Mrs. Todd. ','2005-04-19 21:53:05','2005-04-19 21:55:04',NULL,18),(719,47,399,'To make us consider our starting text a \"deep thought\" that deserves exposition and fine analysis. ','2005-04-19 21:52:59','2005-04-19 21:56:45',NULL,17),(720,47,394,'I finally looked at the facsimile edition and I\'m... stunned. The poems look nothing like the transcriptions. They simply aren\'t the same thing. I think now that my movie will have to be an edition of Dickinson\'s poems, maybe I can call it \"Fascicle.\". You can see my failed efforts to capture something like the real text here (best viewed with \"Show deletes\" off, but a dismal failure in any form), but I finally gave up and posted a jpeg of the facsimile. Even that\'s just a copy of a copy. Tomorrow I\'m flying to Harvard to see the real thing. I WILL see the real thing, I have to. Meanwhile, I\'m still working on making a proper IVANHOE move. There has to be something I can do that will open more possibilities than letter-finding.','2005-04-19 23:58:22','2005-04-20 00:46:41',NULL,17),(721,47,409,'Pardon my intrusion; I assure you it will be only momentary. But I have been made aware of an attack against my good name as well as that of my close friend, Ezra Pound. I feel it is my duty as a responsible critic to offer some reply to the needless disdain for formal analysis expressed by the person identifying himself as \"Tim.\" I thank you for your generous attention.','2005-04-20 00:54:14','2005-04-20 00:58:09',NULL,17),(722,47,408,'Changes to the poems? Yes! Lies? Very likely!\n\nBut a properly historicized account will realize that these editorial interventions served a purpose! That of getting the poems into the hands of readers! That we can now critique such moves is a testament, primarily, to the fact that these changes worked!\n\nMary Loomis Todd is the crucial figure here, far moreso than TW Higginson.','2005-04-20 00:37:38','2005-04-20 01:02:26',NULL,18),(723,47,396,'In anticipation of our analysis of the newly discovered Dickinson poem, I\'ve uncovered some recent research on his work.','2005-04-20 01:21:50','2005-04-20 01:33:21',NULL,0),(725,47,409,'As author of The Waste Land, as well as an employee of Faber and Faber, I know well the power of a good editor. Shall we read for content now?','2005-04-20 17:00:54','2005-04-20 17:10:23',NULL,17),(726,47,409,'Editors are also important for emmending errant texts. I believe this elaborate display system of yours had some hand in undermining my previous move. See it now as it was originally intended.','2005-04-20 17:11:28','2005-04-20 17:14:19',NULL,17),(727,47,399,'To defend my manifesto against Kaufman\'s intellectually irresponsible critique. To move beyond my admittedly silly--but also ludic!--references to grenades and polluted H2O.','2005-04-20 17:30:56','2005-04-20 17:38:02',NULL,17),(728,47,399,'To force Kaufmann to reckon with my argument. He\'s added his beloved dashes, but now he must explain the importance of his move; and why such a move was essential before considering the text\'s thematics or its philosophical argument/meditation.','2005-04-20 17:46:43','2005-04-20 17:51:17',NULL,17),(729,47,394,'I\'m sorry my involvement in this game has become such a source of contention. I\'ve just been swept away in my excitment 