rent flow of play that seems far too esoteric (and uninteresting to me in its obtuse, overwrought rhetoric).  I plan on creating two roles, one that will play along philosophically by utilizing some Lacanian notions of the real (need), imaginary (demand), and symbolic (desire), yet try to introduce no 20th century documents, hence the John Milton aspect.  The other will be a more practical, playful, and deflating character.',-9191527,-103,1),(332,'The Librarian','Glasses, books, etc.','Inspired by the PS 3537 .T3 move, which immediately brought to mind--since I am a library employee--that the number matches a call number format (turns out to be an edition of \"Of Mice and Men\").  This character will introduce documents of a hopefully less academic nature with a healthy bit of good-natured sarcasm for my more high-minded fellow players.  To try and employ a little silliness to make the (to me) non-sensical moves of others a little more comprehendible--and bearable. [I certainly sound put-out by the current run of gameplay, but if IVANHOE is a game, and supposed to be enjoyable, then many of the moves thus far strike me as neither fun nor productive; surprisingly so, since I usually am on the same page as the real people in game 1.  Provocation is a part of IVANHOE, too, I am discovering!]',-4230285,-8382131,1),(333,'Joseph Gilbert','','',-256,-16776961,1),(334,'xyz','dummy role to anonymously look in on game 2','to look and not to touch',-8362419,-8362419,1),(335,'Cory MacLauchlin','','',-256,-16776961,1),(336,'donna di morte','In Rosetti\'s poems woman is consistently placed as the matrix of life and death.  She is responsible for the fall and yet she is the bearer of life.  This paradoxical role seems to gain a stasis within portrainture and thereby enable Rossetti to exploit and tease out it poetic implications.  Isn\'t portraiture a kind of sustained non-life, a published death?  By virtue of its non-dynamic quality it freezes life and therefore takes it away.  Then what is the artist\'s role in portraiture?  Does he impose death on woman thereby somehow avoid death through an unseen, unstatic rememberence of the creator by the onlooker?  Does the gender relation in western art of woman as muse and man as creator invert social roles as a retaliation against the belief system of woman as causer of death?  These are the questions on Donna di Morte\'s mind.   ','To draw attention to the implicit codes/lines between art (portraiture) and the life cycle.  To explore how gender, artistic roles, and the genre of portraiture address and assign responsibility for the fall of \"man\" and the condition of mortality.  ',-256,-16776961,1),(337,'Amy Wentworth','','',-256,-16776961,1),(338,'Salome','Shy.  Prone to the sensual.  Angry.  ','To behead and find truth.  ',-256,-16776961,1),(339,'The Popular Review','A collaborative effort to critique the poetry that appears in this ludic-interpretive space, with an eye towards moving away from Victorian blandness...	','Comment, mock, critique, offend.',-8382131,-4249997,1),(340,'John Havard','','',-256,-16776961,1),(341,'HAZZ0305#','','',-4249997,-8368871,1),(342,'Cory MacLauchlin','','',-256,-16776961,1),(343,'Pedro','The valet of the narrator of Poe\'s \"The Oval Portrait.\" ','Use the scene of portraiture in Poe\'s story as a sort of primal scene to understand the other moments of ekphrasis within the game.',-13369447,-13369549,1),(344,'Christopher Forster','','',-256,-16776961,1),(345,'W~HAZ1830/#05','William Hazlitt\'s cryogenically frozen head is trying to speak to us! As the storage vaults of Gusto Cryogenics TM slip into meltdown, electorlysis partially jolts Hazlitt\'s mind back into life. In an effort to recover his now disintegrated eyes (and testicles) he tries to plug back into his reflections on portraiture. Comining his former thoughts with his responses to whatever he finds in this twenty-first century discourse field, he tries his best to recover his life through language.','